&gt;&gt; Kate Zwaard: Thank
you so much, Meghan.

00:00:50.600 --> 00:00:54.170
I'm thrilled to be here
to open today's events.

00:00:54.170 --> 00:00:55.650
I'm Kate Zwaard, the Library

00:00:55.650 --> 00:00:58.160
of Congress's Director
of Digital Strategy.

00:00:58.160 --> 00:01:01.120
And on behalf of the
Library of Congress, LC Labs,

00:01:01.120 --> 00:01:03.900
the National Museum of African
American History and Culture,

00:01:03.900 --> 00:01:05.760
and JSTOR, I'd like
to welcome everybody

00:01:05.760 --> 00:01:07.710
to the Coolidge Auditorium.

00:01:07.710 --> 00:01:09.120
We're excited to
be able to share

00:01:09.120 --> 00:01:12.730
with you today a week's
worth of very focused work.

00:01:12.730 --> 00:01:16.790
As you all know, Dr. Hayden
has brought a new vision

00:01:16.790 --> 00:01:20.290
to the Library that we be
more user-centered and focused

00:01:20.290 --> 00:01:22.150
on how we can reach
more people and interact

00:01:22.150 --> 00:01:23.710
with them at a deeper level.

00:01:23.710 --> 00:01:25.010
And technology, I think,

00:01:25.010 --> 00:01:27.880
is a really great enabler
of that kind of work.

00:01:27.880 --> 00:01:30.790
This event highlights how
we can effectively partner

00:01:30.790 --> 00:01:33.010
with our users and
create prototypes

00:01:33.010 --> 00:01:35.740
that will make us more
effective and efficient.

00:01:35.740 --> 00:01:38.880
We'll be publishing a digital
strategy for the Library

00:01:38.880 --> 00:01:42.310
of Congress in September
which will describe our plans

00:01:42.310 --> 00:01:44.700
for reaching more
users with technology

00:01:44.700 --> 00:01:48.890
and enabling further
access to our materials.

00:01:48.890 --> 00:01:50.860
To accomplish that work
we're going to lean on labs

00:01:50.860 --> 00:01:53.940
and their ability to try new
things and test our assumptions.

00:01:53.940 --> 00:01:58.560
One of the things I love about
the culture of labs is our --

00:01:58.560 --> 00:02:00.320
that we do things in the open

00:02:00.320 --> 00:02:03.270
so that while we're learning
we're helping other learn.

00:02:03.270 --> 00:02:06.310
So we've learned to much from
JSTOR Labs here this week.

00:02:06.310 --> 00:02:07.650
We're thrilled that
they're here with us.

00:02:07.650 --> 00:02:12.820
So that's a great, great segue
into the past week and today.

00:02:12.820 --> 00:02:15.730
It's been a lively week
of looking at collections

00:02:15.730 --> 00:02:19.780
and new ways of engaging users
inside and outside of our walls

00:02:19.780 --> 00:02:21.580
and of flash-building.

00:02:21.580 --> 00:02:24.490
It's been a week of
shared learning and a week

00:02:24.490 --> 00:02:25.990
of demonstrating the power

00:02:25.990 --> 00:02:28.490
of computational
access to collections.

00:02:28.490 --> 00:02:30.820
We love thinking about the
different ways our collections

00:02:30.820 --> 00:02:35.170
