00:08:54.050 --> 00:08:55.560
Okay. So LC Labs.

00:08:55.560 --> 00:08:56.860
Who are we?

00:08:56.860 --> 00:08:58.160
Where did we come from?

00:08:58.160 --> 00:09:01.740
Two years ago, a little over two
years ago now, we were formed

00:09:01.740 --> 00:09:04.220
and we hosted an event
called Collections as Data,

00:09:04.220 --> 00:09:06.290
and we've actually done
that now two years running.

00:09:06.290 --> 00:09:09.410
And the point of Collections
as Data, if any of you went,

00:09:09.410 --> 00:09:14.050
was an all-day symposium
talking about what does it mean

00:09:14.050 --> 00:09:18.810
to use data in cultural heritage
institutions, to get the public

00:09:18.810 --> 00:09:21.480
to use it, what types of
possibilities are there

00:09:21.480 --> 00:09:23.940
for thinking about
how to interact

00:09:23.940 --> 00:09:26.650
with collections online
in different ways.

00:09:26.650 --> 00:09:29.670
And the first two years, the
symposiums were very talky,

00:09:29.670 --> 00:09:30.970
just like I'm doing now.

00:09:30.970 --> 00:09:32.650
You know, it was a lot of
experts coming together

00:09:32.650 --> 00:09:34.970
to discuss these
really important issues.

00:09:34.970 --> 00:09:37.020
What we wanted to do this
year was take a spin off

00:09:37.020 --> 00:09:41.510
of Collections as Data and
actually just build something.

00:09:41.510 --> 00:09:43.610
So that's kind of
the -- I would say

00:09:43.610 --> 00:09:46.670
that in some ways this is
an unofficial third year

00:09:46.670 --> 00:09:47.970
of Collections as Data,

00:09:47.970 --> 00:09:49.760
but we're taking all the
lessons we've learned

00:09:49.760 --> 00:09:54.830
and actually incorporating
them into the way that we work.

00:09:54.830 --> 00:09:58.010
So what do I mean by
Collections as Data?

00:09:58.010 --> 00:10:02.380
This is an example here of a
tutorial of how to use our API

00:10:02.380 --> 00:10:04.520
if you were investigating
our baseball collections

00:10:04.520 --> 00:10:06.460
which we have many of.

00:10:06.460 --> 00:10:08.760
So one of the things
that we know is

00:10:08.760 --> 00:10:11.780
that people are aware
perhaps of what an API is.

00:10:11.780 --> 00:10:13.080
It's the underlayer

00:10:13.080 --> 00:10:15.370
of information that's
underneath a website

00:10:15.370 --> 00:10:17.660
that you can make calls to.

00:10:17.660 --> 00:10:19.900
But there's some
intimidation of what it means

00:10:19.900 --> 00:10:23.020
or how it could possibly be
useful to someone who happens

00:10:23.020 --> 00:10:24.940
to stumble upon our Lab site.

00:10:24.940 --> 00:10:27.620
So we've done a lot of work on
our site on a page called LC

00:10:27.620 --> 00:10:31.210
for Robots of tutorials
for you to learn how

00:10:31.210 --> 00:10:33.630
to perhaps investigate
our collections

00:10:33.630 --> 00:10:35.600
through the data itself.

00:10:35.600 --> 00:10:38.220
And I encourage you
to look at that

00:10:38.220 --> 00:10:40.520
if you get inspired
by this event.

00:10:44.110 --> 00:10:47.480
This is another example
of Collections as Data.

00:10:48.870 --> 00:10:52.640
This is an example of a
product that was built

00:10:52.640 --> 00:10:54.110
by our Innovator-in-Residence,

00:10:54.110 --> 00:10:55.900
so this is a program
that we started.

00:10:55.900 --> 00:10:58.070
And our current
Innovator-in-Residence is the

00:10:58.070 --> 00:10:59.550
Data Artist, Jer Thorp.

00:10:59.550 --> 00:11:02.910
And the idea behind the
Innovator-in-Residence Program

00:11:02.910 --> 00:11:07.510
is to try to inspire people to
think about collections and how

00:11:07.510 --> 00:11:11.040
to explore them serendipitously
in innovative ways.

00:11:11.040 --> 00:11:12.800
And underlying that is data.

00:11:12.800 --> 00:11:17.040
So this example is the Library
of Color that Jer built.

00:11:17.040 --> 00:11:19.770
And what you're seeing
right now is an example

00:11:19.770 --> 00:11:24.170
of a visual collection
where he took information

00:11:24.170 --> 00:11:29.500
from every single record
from prints and photographs

00:11:29.500 --> 00:11:32.910
and essentially compared
this to --

00:11:33.940 --> 00:11:37.180
took words that you could
extrapolate to color

00:11:37.180 --> 00:11:40.200
and then visualized those
colors into a rainbow.

00:11:40.200 --> 00:11:41.550
And this is a screenshot.

00:11:41.550 --> 00:11:44.120
But if you were to use a
strapdown, for example,

00:11:44.120 --> 00:11:47.840
and look at our literature
collection visualized in color,

00:11:47.840 --> 00:11:51.000
you'd essentially see blue
and black because it turns

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:55.590
out that a lot of titles of
books tend to represent darkness

00:11:55.590 --> 00:11:57.750
or the ocean or something
like that.

00:11:57.750 --> 00:12:00.910
So you can actually, I think,
intuitively work your way

00:12:00.910 --> 00:12:03.480
through the collections
and start

00:12:03.480 --> 00:12:10.630
to extrapolate some theories
around formats and titles,

00:12:10.630 --> 00:12:13.090
plus it's just beautiful,
which is also fun

00:12:13.090 --> 00:12:15.670
and valid in its own right.

00:12:15.670 --> 00:12:19.170
This is another take on
exploring the Library by color.

00:12:19.170 --> 00:12:22.550
This is an experiment that
exists on our Experiments page

