00:22:26.050 --> 00:22:27.350
&gt;&gt; Courtney Bellizzi:
Good morning.

00:22:27.350 --> 00:22:28.730
So we're going to start with
our history collections,

00:22:28.730 --> 00:22:31.660
and since it's All Star week
it's only appropriate to start

00:22:31.660 --> 00:22:34.030
with a collection object that
harkens back to the beginning

00:22:34.030 --> 00:22:35.510
of the All Star Games.

00:22:35.510 --> 00:22:39.260
This pennant from about 1933
celebrates the Negro League's

00:22:39.260 --> 00:22:41.010
East-West All Star Game.

00:22:41.010 --> 00:22:42.460
The Negro Leagues established

00:22:42.460 --> 00:22:46.560
in 1885 gave African American
ballplayers who, due to racism,

00:22:46.560 --> 00:22:49.250
were not accepted to play in
other major and minor leagues,

00:22:49.250 --> 00:22:50.970
a chance to play professionally.

00:22:50.970 --> 00:22:56.020
The East-West All Star Game
began in 1933, the same year

00:22:56.020 --> 00:22:58.880
that the MLB All Star
Game was established.

00:22:58.880 --> 00:23:04.610
The game was generated to
start as a way for the owners

00:23:04.610 --> 00:23:07.780
to generate money essentially.

00:23:07.780 --> 00:23:10.490
But the game became
so much more.

00:23:10.490 --> 00:23:13.140
It was a way to help legitimize
the Negro League teams

00:23:13.140 --> 00:23:16.270
and the African American
professional baseball players.

00:23:16.270 --> 00:23:18.300
The game was the
preeminent sporting event

00:23:18.300 --> 00:23:19.600
for African Americans.

00:23:19.600 --> 00:23:22.280
Celebrities like Count
Basie, Alice Fitzgerald,

00:23:22.280 --> 00:23:24.560
Joe Lewis would attend,
and Lena Horne even threw

00:23:24.560 --> 00:23:27.890
out the first pitch of the
very first All Star Game.

00:23:27.890 --> 00:23:29.950
And though these games were
celebrated, they still stood

00:23:29.950 --> 00:23:32.050
as a stark reminder that
professional baseball,

00:23:32.050 --> 00:23:35.920
like many aspects of American
society, was segregated.

00:23:35.920 --> 00:23:39.530
When we look at the datapoints,
the term segregation is used

00:23:39.530 --> 00:23:42.750
to convey this very
important aspect of history.

00:23:42.750 --> 00:23:45.340
The term also links
us to our next object,

00:23:45.340 --> 00:23:48.290
a poster about the integration
of the Detroit Tigers.

00:23:48.290 --> 00:23:50.500
This is nicely [inaudible] done.

00:23:50.500 --> 00:23:54.630
In 1947, Jackie Robinson
stepped onto the field to play

00:23:54.630 --> 00:23:55.930
for the Brooklyn Dodgers

00:23:55.930 --> 00:23:57.900
and desegregated
Major League Baseball.

00:23:57.900 --> 00:23:59.650
Not all teams were
quick to follow.

00:23:59.650 --> 00:24:03.700
In 1958, the Detroit Tigers
were the second-to-last team

00:24:03.700 --> 00:24:07.400
to integrate when Ozzie
Virgil, Senior joined the team.

00:24:07.400 --> 00:24:09.510
Virgil was born in
the Dominican Republic

00:24:09.510 --> 00:24:11.650
and was the first
person of African descent

00:24:11.650 --> 00:24:14.710
to join the Tigers, and was
also the first Dominican

00:24:14.710 --> 00:24:16.010
to play in MLB.

00:24:16.010 --> 00:24:20.830
On June 6, 1958, Virgil went
five for five in his debut

00:24:20.830 --> 00:24:24.320
with the Tigers, and despite
occurring more than 10 years

00:24:24.320 --> 00:24:27.090
after Robinson's first
game, the integration

00:24:27.090 --> 00:24:29.120
of the Tigers was
still met with protest

00:24:29.120 --> 00:24:30.680
from staunch segregationists,

00:24:30.680 --> 00:24:34.530
including Detroit City
Council Member Billy Rogell.

00:24:34.530 --> 00:24:38.430
He was also a former shortstop
for the Detroit Tigers.

00:24:38.430 --> 00:24:40.050
Rogell opposed Virgil's
appointment

00:24:40.050 --> 00:24:42.200
to the team vehemently.

00:24:42.200 --> 00:24:45.260
And this poster here sends a
clear message to Mr. Rogell

00:24:45.260 --> 00:24:48.150
about his policies and
beliefs and gives us a glimpse

00:24:48.150 --> 00:24:52.330
into race relations in the
city of Detroit in 1958.

00:24:52.330 --> 00:24:54.610
As you can see, several
subjects have been attributed

00:24:54.610 --> 00:24:56.480
to this object including
segregation,

00:24:56.480 --> 00:24:58.740
civil rights, and
race relations.

00:24:58.740 --> 00:25:00.450
Using the term race relations,

00:25:00.450 --> 00:25:02.880
we can move to our next
related object type,

00:25:02.880 --> 00:25:05.700
a magazine from 1960
featuring notable African

00:25:05.700 --> 00:25:07.170
American athletes.

00:25:07.170 --> 00:25:10.560
As professional sports
became integrated,

00:25:10.560 --> 00:25:13.770
African American athletes
soon became household names.

00:25:13.770 --> 00:25:16.550
Though African American
athletes became mainstream,

00:25:16.550 --> 00:25:20.190
they were still viewed as other
as evidenced by this issue

00:25:20.190 --> 00:25:23.030
of <i>Sport Magazine </i>from 1960.

00:25:23.030 --> 00:25:26.910
The title of the issue
is "Sport, Special Issue,

00:25:26.910 --> 00:25:28.330
the Negro in American Sport."

00:25:28.330 --> 00:25:30.590
And it still conveys this idea

00:25:30.590 --> 00:25:32.580
that African American
athletes needed to be looked

00:25:32.580 --> 00:25:35.600
at separately from their
white counterparts.

00:25:35.600 --> 00:25:37.870
The term race relations
was used for this object

00:25:37.870 --> 00:25:40.870
because <i>Sports Magazine </i>was
founded in 1946 and was one

00:25:40.870 --> 00:25:43.190
of the first national
sports publications,

00:25:43.190 --> 00:25:44.660
and serves as an example

00:25:44.660 --> 00:25:46.960
of how African American
athletes' achievement were

00:25:46.960 --> 00:25:48.850
covered by mass media.

00:25:48.850 --> 00:25:51.720
The magazine features
notable athletes include Wilt

00:25:51.720 --> 00:25:55.950
Chamberlain, Willie Mays, Althea
Gibson, and Jackie Robinson.

00:25:55.950 --> 00:26:00.020
From a data perspective, all of
these athletes become subjects

00:26:00.020 --> 00:26:02.820
of the collection object,
so that this object appears

00:26:02.820 --> 00:26:05.900
when any of the aforementioned
names are searched.

00:26:05.900 --> 00:26:07.980
Let us look at the
datapoint Jackie Robinson

00:26:07.980 --> 00:26:09.810
to move along to
our next dataset.

