00:26:42.460 --> 00:26:44.780
of Jackie Robinson
and Harry Owens.

00:26:44.780 --> 00:26:46.430
Here Robinson is out of uniform,

00:26:46.430 --> 00:26:48.400
receiving a Lifetime
Membership Award

00:26:48.400 --> 00:26:51.130
to the Irene Kaufmann
Settlement House in Pittsburgh,

00:26:51.130 --> 00:26:53.490
Pennsylvania for
his charity work.

00:26:53.490 --> 00:26:54.960
The photograph was taken

00:26:54.960 --> 00:26:59.220
by a community photographer
named Charles "Teenie" Harris.

00:26:59.220 --> 00:27:01.840
Harris was founded --
Harris had a connection

00:27:01.840 --> 00:27:05.020
to baseball actually because he
helped found and was a player

00:27:05.020 --> 00:27:07.600
for the Crawford Colored Giants

00:27:07.600 --> 00:27:09.640
who later became the
Pittsburgh Crawfords.

00:27:09.640 --> 00:27:12.240
So there's another little
baseball connection in there.

00:27:12.240 --> 00:27:15.760
But Harris was known as
"One-Shot," not in a reference

00:27:15.760 --> 00:27:18.860
to his baseball career, but in
reference to his photography.

00:27:18.860 --> 00:27:23.270
His photography mainly
focused on the Hill District

00:27:23.270 --> 00:27:27.150
which is a African American
community in Pittsburgh,

00:27:27.150 --> 00:27:29.800
and his more than
80,000 images provide one

00:27:29.800 --> 00:27:31.670
of the most complete
documentations

00:27:31.670 --> 00:27:34.640
of a minority community
in the United States.

00:27:34.640 --> 00:27:37.460
When cataloging this
photograph, it's important

00:27:37.460 --> 00:27:40.290
that the data not only leads
us to these researchers,

00:27:40.290 --> 00:27:43.410
to Jackie Robinson, but
also to "Teenie" Harris,

00:27:43.410 --> 00:27:45.810
the notable community
photographer.

00:27:45.810 --> 00:27:50.610
Using another datapoint from
this object, the date, 1954,

00:27:50.610 --> 00:27:53.210
it will lead us to
another photograph taken

00:27:53.210 --> 00:27:57.290
by another community
photographer, Ernest C. Withers.

00:27:57.290 --> 00:28:01.140
Around 1954, Ernest C.
Withers took this portrait

00:28:01.140 --> 00:28:02.670
of Connie Morgan.

00:28:02.670 --> 00:28:04.470
Withers, a well-known
photojournalist,

00:28:04.470 --> 00:28:06.490
documented African
American communities

00:28:06.490 --> 00:28:09.070
in the segregated
South for 60 years.

00:28:09.070 --> 00:28:11.000
Morgan was the third woman

00:28:11.000 --> 00:28:13.260
to play professional
baseball in the Negro League.

00:28:13.260 --> 00:28:16.090
She joined the Indianapolis
Crowns in 1954

00:28:16.090 --> 00:28:20.160
as a second baseman and
replaced the first woman

00:28:20.160 --> 00:28:23.360
who joined the Leagues,
Toni Stone.

00:28:23.360 --> 00:28:27.290
Though many saw having women
join the teams as a gimmick

00:28:27.290 --> 00:28:29.470
to increase sales after
the integration with MLB,

00:28:29.470 --> 00:28:33.060
many journalists who covered
the Negro Leagues also wrote

00:28:33.060 --> 00:28:36.070
about the women's skill
and talent as players.

00:28:36.070 --> 00:28:40.240
For example, an article covering
the Crowns' game on May 29,

00:28:40.240 --> 00:28:44.800
1954, featured in the <i>Afro
American </i>, noted, quote,

00:28:44.800 --> 00:28:48.570
"Morgan electrified over
6000 fans when she went far

00:28:48.570 --> 00:28:50.620
to her right to make
a sensational stop,

00:28:50.620 --> 00:28:52.930
slip the shortstop, Bill Holder,

00:28:52.930 --> 00:28:54.960
and started a lightning
double-play

00:28:54.960 --> 00:28:57.670
against the Birmingham
Barons," end quote.

00:28:57.670 --> 00:29:01.050
Morgan's great double play
excited this large community

00:29:01.050 --> 00:29:02.350
of fans.

00:29:02.350 --> 00:29:03.650
And what we find that's

00:29:03.650 --> 00:29:05.680
so prevalent throughout our
Museum's Baseball Collections is

00:29:05.680 --> 00:29:07.510
this tie to community.

00:29:07.510 --> 00:29:10.630
This time, let us turn to
the object type Portraits

00:29:10.630 --> 00:29:13.510
to see how this portrait of
Connie Morgan can link us

00:29:13.510 --> 00:29:15.490
to another object
reflecting community

00:29:15.490 --> 00:29:17.790
within the Museum's collections.

00:29:21.040 --> 00:29:22.610
&gt;&gt; Emily Houf: The object
type Portraits brings us

00:29:22.610 --> 00:29:24.270
to the collection
of the photographer,

00:29:24.270 --> 00:29:26.510
the Reverend Henry C. Anderson.

00:29:26.510 --> 00:29:30.270
Anderson was the local portrait
photographer in Greenville,

00:29:30.270 --> 00:29:34.640
Mississippi from 1947
through the 1970s.

00:29:34.640 --> 00:29:36.600
Nearly every m4mber
of the black community

00:29:36.600 --> 00:29:39.290
of Greenville had their portrait
taken by Reverend Anderson

00:29:39.290 --> 00:29:41.400
at one point or another.

00:29:41.400 --> 00:29:44.650
Anderson documented all
aspects of Greenville's family

00:29:44.650 --> 00:29:47.870
and community life during
Jim Crow segregation,

00:29:47.870 --> 00:29:51.780
including new babies, birthdays,
weddings, anniversaries,

00:29:51.780 --> 00:29:56.540
graduations, church groups,
community clubs, and, of course,

00:29:56.540 --> 00:30:00.630
the Little League teams
like this one here.

00:30:00.630 --> 00:30:03.720
So we've just seen how our
subject terms can take us

00:30:03.720 --> 00:30:06.420
through several community
photographers.

00:30:06.420 --> 00:30:10.100
But if we use the classification
Media Arts Photography,

00:30:10.100 --> 00:30:14.050
where all of our photographs
and images are grouped under,

00:30:14.050 --> 00:30:18.300
we can expand and will
find the IGME Collection

00:30:18.300 --> 00:30:21.920
of Hip-Hop Photography
where perhaps, surprisingly,

00:30:21.920 --> 00:30:25.400
we also find baseball.

00:30:25.400 --> 00:30:31.290
This leads us to the Culture
section of our objects.

00:30:31.290 --> 00:30:37.230
In this photograph of KRS-One
taken by Al Pereira in 1991,

00:30:37.230 --> 00:30:39.470
the rapper sports
the iconic pinstripes

00:30:39.470 --> 00:30:41.310
of the New York Yankees.

00:30:41.310 --> 00:30:45.820
KRS-One is an influential
MC from the South Bronx.

00:30:45.820 --> 00:30:48.320
He started his career as
part of the duo Boogey

00:30:48.320 --> 00:30:51.820
Down Productions before going
solo after the shooting death

00:30:51.820 --> 00:30:55.000
of his partner, DJ
Scott La Rock.

00:30:55.000 --> 00:30:58.560
And being from the South
Bronx, KRS-One's affinity

00:30:58.560 --> 00:31:01.250
for Yankees' gear
signifies his ties

00:31:01.250 --> 00:31:03.350
to the birthplace of hip-hop.

00:31:03.350 --> 00:31:06.560
Using athletic wear, and
baseball teams in particular,

00:31:06.560 --> 00:31:12.440
in this way, is a common style
for hip-hop stars like KRS-One.

00:31:12.440 --> 00:31:15.450
And if we follow the
term hip-hop we'll see

00:31:15.450 --> 00:31:18.690
another example.

00:31:18.690 --> 00:31:22.190
This is perhaps the supreme
example of the intersections

00:31:22.190 --> 00:31:27.350
of baseball, music, and fashion,
the iconic baseball cap.

00:31:27.350 --> 00:31:29.750
I learned recently, yesterday,

00:31:29.750 --> 00:31:33.540
that baseball historians
credit Tom Selleck

00:31:33.540 --> 00:31:37.580
with popularizing the
off-the-field baseball cap trend

00:31:37.580 --> 00:31:39.370
in the 1970s.

00:31:39.370 --> 00:31:40.910
But I think we can all agree

00:31:40.910 --> 00:31:43.410
that hip-hop is largely
responsible

00:31:43.410 --> 00:31:45.550
for the longevity of the trend.

00:31:45.550 --> 00:31:48.980
This purple Atlanta Braves
cap from the rapper Big Boy,

00:31:48.980 --> 00:31:51.210
who is one-half of
the group Outcast,

00:31:51.210 --> 00:31:54.780
was made by the preeminent
manufacturer of baseball caps,

00:31:54.780 --> 00:32:00.450
New Era Cap Company, which has
been making caps since 1920.

00:32:00.450 --> 00:32:04.490
This particular hat was
a limited release in 2013

00:32:04.490 --> 00:32:08.370
in conjunction with Big Boy's
solo album, "Vicious Lies

00:32:08.370 --> 00:32:10.250
and Dangerous Rumors."

00:32:10.250 --> 00:32:15.770
In early June, 2013, fans who
attended a CD signing by Big Boy

00:32:15.770 --> 00:32:20.200
at the New Era store in Atlanta
also received this limited

00:32:20.200 --> 00:32:23.120
edition hat inspired
by the album.

00:32:23.120 --> 00:32:26.690
Big Boy and Outcast
is known as the group

00:32:26.690 --> 00:32:29.610
that brought southern
hip-hop into the mainstream,

00:32:29.610 --> 00:32:33.810
and Big Boy is seldom seen
without his signature Braves hat

00:32:33.810 --> 00:32:36.700
to rep his home town of Atlanta.

00:32:36.700 --> 00:32:39.680
This hat has the
sub-classification,

00:32:39.680 --> 00:32:41.580
Clothing Fashion.

00:32:41.580 --> 00:32:45.390
But if we follow the main class,
Clothing, or the subject term,

00:32:45.390 --> 00:32:48.790
Clothing and Dress, we end up
back in the traditional world

00:32:48.790 --> 00:32:53.230
of baseball with this Cardinals'
jersey that was [inaudible] worn

00:32:53.230 --> 00:32:56.180
by Curt Flood in 1966.

00:32:56.180 --> 00:32:59.050
Flood was an All-Star
player and a centerfielder

00:32:59.050 --> 00:33:00.540
for the St. Louis Cardinals.

00:33:00.540 --> 00:33:04.760
He won Gold Glove seven
consecutive seasons

00:33:04.760 --> 00:33:08.560
from 1963 to 1969.

00:33:08.560 --> 00:33:11.150
And during Flood's 11
seasons on the team,

00:33:11.150 --> 00:33:15.870
the Cards won three pennants and
earned two World Series rings.

00:33:15.870 --> 00:33:19.230
When Flood refused to accept a
trade away from the Cardinals

00:33:19.230 --> 00:33:23.790
in 1969, his challenge to the
Reserve Clause helped in usher

00:33:23.790 --> 00:33:27.560
in the Free Agency System
which was transformative

00:33:27.560 --> 00:33:29.780
for the culture of baseball.

00:33:29.780 --> 00:33:33.510
Flood wrote a letter to the
Baseball Commissioner reading,

00:33:33.510 --> 00:33:35.760
"After 12 years in
the Major Leagues,

00:33:35.760 --> 00:33:38.910
I do not feel I am a piece
of property to be bought

00:33:38.910 --> 00:33:42.180
and sold irrespective
of my wishes.

00:33:42.180 --> 00:33:44.220
I believe that any
system which produces

00:33:44.220 --> 00:33:48.040
that result violates my
basic rights as a citizen

00:33:48.040 --> 00:33:51.240
and is inconsistent with the
laws of the United States

00:33:51.240 --> 00:33:53.510
and of the several states."

00:33:53.510 --> 00:33:57.560
Flood's subsequent lawsuit
again Major League Baseball was

00:33:57.560 --> 00:34:01.780
unsuccessfully argued in front
of the Supreme Court in 1972

00:34:01.780 --> 00:34:03.730
which sided with the League.

00:34:03.730 --> 00:34:08.000
But it eventually led to the end

00:34:08.000 --> 00:34:12.870
of the reserve system
a few years later.

00:34:12.870 --> 00:34:17.270
Twenty-six years later, with
the Curt Flood Act of 1998,

00:34:17.270 --> 00:34:19.710
Congress declared Major
League Baseball subject

00:34:19.710 --> 00:34:23.510
to antitrust laws like
any other corporation.

00:34:23.510 --> 00:34:27.100
Flood is also responsible
for the 10-5 Rule,

00:34:27.100 --> 00:34:30.080
which is often known as the
Curt Flood Rule which states

00:34:30.080 --> 00:34:33.600
that when a player has play for
a team for five straight years,

00:34:33.600 --> 00:34:37.150
and played in the Major League
for a total of 10 years,

00:34:37.150 --> 00:34:41.680
they have to give the club
their consent to be traded.

00:34:41.680 --> 00:34:43.970
Although Flood's
legacy is larger

00:34:43.970 --> 00:34:46.670
than the time he spent playing
with the Cardinals, well,

00:34:46.670 --> 00:34:51.030
we can use the team name to
follow to our final object,

00:34:51.030 --> 00:34:53.590
Minnie Roundtree's Radio.

00:34:54.630 --> 00:34:59.010
Mini Roundtree was a
diehard Cardinals fan,

00:34:59.010 --> 00:35:02.090
living in the rural
community of Lyles Station

00:35:02.090 --> 00:35:05.340
in Gibson County, Indiana.

00:35:05.340 --> 00:35:07.790
Her husband, Herman,
bought her this radio

00:35:07.790 --> 00:35:10.010
so that she could listen
to the games and keep

00:35:10.010 --> 00:35:11.970
up with her favorite team.

00:35:11.970 --> 00:35:15.340
And the story of Minnie and
her radio is a favorite of mine

00:35:15.340 --> 00:35:18.090
because she reminds me of
my own grandmother who,

00:35:18.090 --> 00:35:21.950
at 94 years old, never
misses a Cardinals game.

