00:54:12.880 --> 00:54:15.080
about those stories and
wanting to be able to tell them.

00:54:15.080 --> 00:54:17.210
I'd go through their
books or their lectures.

00:54:17.210 --> 00:54:19.110
We wanted to find ways
to make it even easier

00:54:19.110 --> 00:54:21.410
for them to do so.

00:54:25.040 --> 00:54:28.950
So that was the work we did
over the past couple of months,

00:54:28.950 --> 00:54:33.320
leading up to Monday when
we all came down here.

00:54:33.320 --> 00:54:36.580
And the first thing we
did on Monday was --

00:54:36.580 --> 00:54:39.650
I think Jaime had a
picture of this as well --

00:54:39.650 --> 00:54:40.950
was lead a Design Jam.

00:54:40.950 --> 00:54:44.900
And these are called a
few different things.

00:54:44.900 --> 00:54:46.630
Sometimes called Design James.

00:54:46.630 --> 00:54:50.790
I've called them Idea Jams,
Design Studios sometimes.

00:54:50.790 --> 00:54:52.570
There are various ways --

00:54:52.570 --> 00:54:55.920
it's a structured
brainstorming technique,

00:54:55.920 --> 00:54:59.250
and there's a few different
steps that you go through.

00:54:59.250 --> 00:55:02.580
And the first one is the one you
see here on these Post-It Notes

00:55:02.580 --> 00:55:07.910
that Jessica, who's awesome, and
in the back, is ably leading.

00:55:07.910 --> 00:55:11.870
An empathy map is a way to
highlight and bring together all

00:55:11.870 --> 00:55:13.420
of that research on users

00:55:13.420 --> 00:55:15.210
and baseball researchers
that we'd done.

00:55:15.210 --> 00:55:18.480
Sort of brainstorming
what are their big goals,

00:55:18.480 --> 00:55:20.170
what are the tasks
that they need to try

00:55:20.170 --> 00:55:21.840
to achieve, what
are the hurdles?

00:55:21.840 --> 00:55:24.520
Because those can spark
ideas for what we can do

00:55:24.520 --> 00:55:27.390
to make -- to help them.

00:55:27.390 --> 00:55:30.000
From there -- this was all --

00:55:30.000 --> 00:55:31.580
this Design Jam was
a couple of hours.

00:55:31.580 --> 00:55:33.720
It was a quick brainstorming
session.

00:55:33.720 --> 00:55:35.630
We did something
called an eight-by-eight

00:55:35.630 --> 00:55:38.050
which are what you see here.

00:55:38.050 --> 00:55:42.620
You see pages and pages
of pieces of paper

00:55:42.620 --> 00:55:47.250
with eight squares and everybody
in the room worked silently.

00:55:47.250 --> 00:55:50.500
Had eight minutes to draw
eight different ideas.

00:55:50.500 --> 00:55:53.840
They then presented their
ideas to the entire room,

00:55:53.840 --> 00:55:56.870
and we did it again
sharing those ideas.

00:55:56.870 --> 00:56:01.340
And it's a really wonderful
way to very quickly come

00:56:01.340 --> 00:56:03.340
up with lots of ideas.

00:56:03.340 --> 00:56:07.490
And these were all based on, and
responding to the empathy map.

00:56:07.490 --> 00:56:09.490
They build on it, helping --

00:56:09.490 --> 00:56:12.170
each one would help a
user achieve their goals

00:56:12.170 --> 00:56:13.470
or overcome a hurdle.

00:56:13.470 --> 00:56:16.800
And some of the ideas
aren't fully formed.

00:56:16.800 --> 00:56:18.310
None of them are fully formed.

00:56:18.310 --> 00:56:20.320
Some of them are
more fully formed.

00:56:20.320 --> 00:56:21.620
But they help each other,

00:56:21.620 --> 00:56:24.500
and it's a very generative
approach to brainstorming.

00:56:24.500 --> 00:56:28.210
We then ended the
Design Jam by dot voting.

00:56:28.210 --> 00:56:30.040
Everybody had three dots,
could choose the things

00:56:30.040 --> 00:56:32.270
that were most exciting,
and that gave us a heat map

00:56:32.270 --> 00:56:35.690
of the ideas that
were most exciting.

00:56:35.690 --> 00:56:41.260
From there -- so we ended that
with five or six general ideas

00:56:41.260 --> 00:56:43.360
that we were excited to explore.

00:56:43.360 --> 00:56:46.670
But we need to have a way
to choose between those.

00:56:46.670 --> 00:56:48.840
And one of the hallmarks, and
one of the important parts

00:56:48.840 --> 00:56:53.160
of these Labs Weeks is
it's focused effort,

00:56:53.160 --> 00:56:55.750
but it's iterative effort,
even within the week.

00:56:55.750 --> 00:56:57.560
It's not just one week of work.

00:56:57.560 --> 00:57:00.360
We've had baseball
researchers coming

00:57:00.360 --> 00:57:03.300
in to pretty much
every day this week,

00:57:03.300 --> 00:57:07.760
and at each step we'd be showing
baseball researchers our works

00:57:07.760 --> 00:57:11.430
in progress, of where we are so
far, and using their feedback

00:57:11.430 --> 00:57:13.140
to help us make decisions.

00:57:13.140 --> 00:57:15.150
So at this point we had,

00:57:15.150 --> 00:57:17.540
we created a set of
paper prototypes.

00:57:17.540 --> 00:57:19.450
And you saw a picture
in Jaime's presentation

00:57:19.450 --> 00:57:22.350
of Grif doing this
on the LC Team.

00:57:22.350 --> 00:57:26.340
Paper prototypes of different
ways that we could go

00:57:26.340 --> 00:57:28.560
about using linked open data

00:57:28.560 --> 00:57:32.430
to help baseball
researchers do this.

00:57:32.430 --> 00:57:33.730
There's a map.

00:57:33.730 --> 00:57:38.050
There was a Chrome filter
that gave us a baseball lens

00:57:38.050 --> 00:57:40.610
when you're reading
about anything.

00:57:40.610 --> 00:57:44.690
And then there's this idea
called cultural history baseball

00:57:44.690 --> 00:57:48.020
cards, and that's the one
that we ended up running with.

00:57:48.020 --> 00:57:49.750
So then the rest of the week --

00:57:49.750 --> 00:57:51.930
so by Tuesday we knew
what we wanted to build.

00:57:51.930 --> 00:57:54.150
It might even have
been Monday afternoon.

00:57:54.150 --> 00:57:57.330
So then it was about rapidly
refining and making --

00:57:57.330 --> 00:57:58.990
turning that idea into a thing

00:57:58.990 --> 00:58:01.910
that actually exists
in the world.

00:58:01.910 --> 00:58:04.390
So this -- so I'll
show you quickly what

00:58:04.390 --> 00:58:05.690
that evolution looked like,

00:58:05.690 --> 00:58:08.440
and then we'll get
to the actual site.

00:58:08.440 --> 00:58:11.610
So this was the Design
Jam sketch.

00:58:11.610 --> 00:58:16.990
You can see it's pretty
unclear what it is.

00:58:16.990 --> 00:58:18.290
It's very sketchy.

00:58:18.290 --> 00:58:20.970
There's a couple -- a
little bit of a flow there.

00:58:20.970 --> 00:58:24.040
And sometimes with these you'll
have multiple sketches all

00:58:24.040 --> 00:58:25.340
talking about the same idea.

00:58:25.340 --> 00:58:26.640
And we'll bring those together.

00:58:26.640 --> 00:58:29.210
That turned into the paper
prototype which turned

00:58:29.210 --> 00:58:34.830
into the first design mock-up
which we'd show on screen

00:58:34.830 --> 00:58:38.030
to users to get feelings
for whether they liked --

00:58:38.030 --> 00:58:39.770
whether the thought the
idea could be useful,

00:58:39.770 --> 00:58:42.060
where they were confused,
what made sense.

00:58:42.060 --> 00:58:43.840
At this point people
were getting confused

00:58:43.840 --> 00:58:46.800
between baseball
cards and car --

00:58:46.800 --> 00:58:50.490
and like they thought this was
a collection of baseball cards.

00:58:50.490 --> 00:58:53.600
They weren't seeing the
links to the materials.

00:58:53.600 --> 00:59:00.740
And there were all sorts
of other problems, too.

00:59:00.740 --> 00:59:02.530
But that's why we
do the research.

00:59:02.530 --> 00:59:04.270
And that makes it kind
of fun and exciting.

00:59:04.270 --> 00:59:07.980
This is a further
refinement of the design.

00:59:07.980 --> 00:59:11.470
And so now you can see
on the baseball card

00:59:11.470 --> 00:59:15.060
for Jackie Robinson, the
cultural history baseball card.

00:59:15.060 --> 00:59:17.110
You know, on a baseball card,
if you're familiar with them,

00:59:17.110 --> 00:59:19.680
there's often physical
-- there's the stats,

00:59:19.680 --> 00:59:24.420
their batting average,
their ERA, year-by-year

00:59:24.420 --> 00:59:27.280
on the lower -- on
the back of the card.

00:59:27.280 --> 00:59:29.780
But on the cultural
history baseball cards,

00:59:29.780 --> 00:59:33.000
you can get that stuff,
those baseball stats

00:59:33.000 --> 00:59:35.980
at baseballreference.com or
any other wonderful place.

00:59:35.980 --> 00:59:38.880
Instead we have stats about
their cultural history.

00:59:38.880 --> 00:59:44.690
So these are links to and stats
about the scholarly articles

00:59:44.690 --> 00:59:47.840
about Jackie Robinson, the
number of photos or videos

00:59:47.840 --> 00:59:50.950
or objects that are available
in the different collections.

00:59:50.950 --> 00:59:54.540
So that's Library of Congress
and Smithsonian, Wikidata.

00:59:54.540 --> 00:59:56.680
And so it sort of
gives a snapshot

00:59:56.680 --> 00:59:58.540
of how much information we have.

00:59:58.540 --> 01:00:00.260
And then you can dive into it.

01:00:00.260 --> 01:00:05.580
So, with that I think we should
switch over to Chrome and see

01:00:05.580 --> 01:00:07.620
where it is, see
what it looks like.

01:00:07.620 --> 01:00:10.780
This is the -- there we go.

01:00:10.780 --> 01:00:13.340
A quick, you know, caveat.

01:00:13.340 --> 01:00:16.880
This is a week of work,
so the way you're going

01:00:16.880 --> 01:00:19.520
to see is definitely
a work in progress.

01:00:19.520 --> 01:00:21.960
There will be parts
that look great.

01:00:21.960 --> 01:00:25.540
There will be some parts that
are a little bit buggy still.

01:00:25.540 --> 01:00:29.530
And you get to do that
when it's only a week.

01:00:29.530 --> 01:00:31.750
We're trying to focus
enough to give an idea

01:00:31.750 --> 01:00:33.210
of what this actually is.

01:00:33.210 --> 01:00:37.680
So what we have is the Cultural
History Baseball Cards brought

01:00:37.680 --> 01:00:40.050
to you by the JSTOR Labs Team.

01:00:40.050 --> 01:00:42.660
And the idea is that
you can pick a player

01:00:42.660 --> 01:00:46.100
or historical figure, see
their cultural history card,

01:00:46.100 --> 01:00:48.580
and then browse through
the primary

01:00:48.580 --> 01:00:51.840
and secondary resources
about them.

01:00:51.840 --> 01:00:55.410
These are organized right
now by the number of articles

01:00:55.410 --> 01:00:57.160
in JSTOR about each of these.

01:00:57.160 --> 01:01:00.240
And what's fun about this, and
if you even show the next 25

01:01:00.240 --> 01:01:03.330
or whatever, first of all
it's not just players,

01:01:03.330 --> 01:01:06.370
your Branch Rickey, your Bill
James, you have Marvin Miller,

01:01:06.370 --> 01:01:10.200
you have -- this is not just
the players of baseball.

01:01:10.200 --> 01:01:13.770
This is the history of
baseball sort of told here,

01:01:13.770 --> 01:01:16.600
which is really exciting.

01:01:16.600 --> 01:01:19.060
We envision, but before we
go live, that would be --

01:01:19.060 --> 01:01:20.640
we'll have more than
just the article,

01:01:20.640 --> 01:01:22.110
number of articles
on this homepage.

01:01:22.110 --> 01:01:24.220
It will include the
number of videos

01:01:24.220 --> 01:01:26.460
and images that we have as well.

01:01:26.460 --> 01:01:29.170
Then when you click through
to an individual file --

01:01:29.170 --> 01:01:30.470
who do we have?

01:01:30.470 --> 01:01:33.540
Ah, Hammered Hank.

01:01:33.540 --> 01:01:36.620
We have their baseball card
that has the data of the number

01:01:36.620 --> 01:01:38.790
of articles and images
and videos

01:01:38.790 --> 01:01:41.470
if we have them,
physical objects.

01:01:41.470 --> 01:01:44.550
We're sort of still working
on the classifications

01:01:44.550 --> 01:01:46.960
and how we map those
to the libraries

01:01:46.960 --> 01:01:48.900
and Smithsonian's
classifications.

01:01:48.900 --> 01:01:51.390
So those are at the top.

01:01:51.390 --> 01:01:52.920
And then you can browse through.

01:01:52.920 --> 01:01:54.500
If you're looking at
articles, you can see all

01:01:54.500 --> 01:01:56.220
of the articles right there.

01:01:56.220 --> 01:01:58.550
Click through them to get
access to them on JSTOR.

01:01:58.550 --> 01:02:03.190
Or if you want to
look at the images,

01:02:03.190 --> 01:02:05.880
it brings together the different
images from all the sources.

01:02:05.880 --> 01:02:08.800
You can browse through those
images and then get access

01:02:08.800 --> 01:02:11.610
to those images where
they're available,

01:02:11.610 --> 01:02:13.310
the high resolution
image perhaps that's

01:02:13.310 --> 01:02:15.850
on the Museum site or
the Library's site.

01:02:15.850 --> 01:02:20.880
Then there are some printed
materials here as well.

01:02:20.880 --> 01:02:22.370
And I'd just encourage --

01:02:22.370 --> 01:02:26.240
I mean, so there's a lot of
exploring that you can do,

01:02:26.240 --> 01:02:28.230
all organized around people.

01:02:28.230 --> 01:02:30.680
When we talk to the user
-- the researchers --

01:02:30.680 --> 01:02:33.640
and one of the things
that led to this was a lot

01:02:33.640 --> 01:02:35.070
of them did want people.

01:02:35.070 --> 01:02:37.850
They were interested in how
to connect the different --

01:02:37.850 --> 01:02:42.450
the materials related
to each person.

01:02:42.450 --> 01:02:46.540
They would say that, you know,
I know I'm doing research on --

01:02:46.540 --> 01:02:49.450
I'm telling this particular
story, and I don't know

01:02:49.450 --> 01:02:51.940
if this archive, you know,
is available at the Hall

01:02:51.940 --> 01:02:53.420
of Fame, is it available here?

01:02:53.420 --> 01:02:55.780
So if I could have a
way to connect those

01:02:55.780 --> 01:02:57.580
and bring those together,
it could be valuable.

01:02:57.580 --> 01:03:00.630
They also described that when
they first start their research,

01:03:00.630 --> 01:03:03.310
they start with the
secondary literature,

01:03:03.310 --> 01:03:07.520
so that would be the
scholarly articles in JSTOR.

01:03:07.520 --> 01:03:09.580
And then they dive
in, do a deep dive

01:03:09.580 --> 01:03:11.280
into the contextual material.

01:03:11.280 --> 01:03:12.580
But that depends.

01:03:12.580 --> 01:03:13.880
For students, they may want --

01:03:13.880 --> 01:03:15.780
may benefit from
seeing the pictures

01:03:15.780 --> 01:03:18.120
that help bring the history
to life and tell some

01:03:18.120 --> 01:03:23.950
of the stories like we heard
just in the presentation

01:03:23.950 --> 01:03:25.560
from the National Museum

01:03:25.560 --> 01:03:27.970
of African American
History and Culture.

01:03:32.080 --> 01:03:33.890
I think that's enough demo.

01:03:33.890 --> 01:03:35.830
We could keep clicking
around and --

01:03:35.830 --> 01:03:38.250
but let's go back
to the presentation

01:03:38.250 --> 01:03:42.060
so we can get to questions.

01:03:42.060 --> 01:03:46.290
One thing I should say is that
this -- I see this right now,

01:03:46.290 --> 01:03:47.850
and the team sees
this right now,

01:03:47.850 --> 01:03:50.630
as probably a little bit
more of a proof of concept

01:03:50.630 --> 01:03:53.250
than full-fledged, you know,

01:03:53.250 --> 01:03:56.540
research tool ready
for heavy lifting.

01:03:56.540 --> 01:04:00.260
This is more of an idea,
an evocation of that idea,

01:04:00.260 --> 01:04:02.440
to help people understand
what it could look like.

01:04:02.440 --> 01:04:03.740
But there's still work to do.

01:04:03.740 --> 01:04:05.750
If you -- oh, I get to click.

01:04:05.750 --> 01:04:07.390
So there's still work to do.

