01:04:42.020 --> 01:04:45.020
Just so share what we've
learned along this way,

01:04:45.020 --> 01:04:46.640
along this journey.

01:04:46.640 --> 01:04:50.600
We do see some opportunity
for further development.

01:04:50.600 --> 01:04:52.170
And the first one is
-- I think for this

01:04:52.170 --> 01:04:55.950
to be a really valuable tool,
the amount of collections

01:04:55.950 --> 01:04:59.410
and data that's included in
it needs to be more robust.

01:04:59.410 --> 01:05:02.400
JSTORs great, the collections
at the Library of Congress

01:05:02.400 --> 01:05:04.220
and the National Museum of
African American History

01:05:04.220 --> 01:05:07.060
and Culture, that's some
really wonderful material.

01:05:07.060 --> 01:05:08.440
But it feels still a little --

01:05:08.440 --> 01:05:11.390
I think there's even more
that we can do by bringing in,

01:05:11.390 --> 01:05:13.810
for example, the Digital
Public Library of America

01:05:13.810 --> 01:05:17.930
or some other materials
and beefing that up.

01:05:17.930 --> 01:05:19.410
So that would be work
that we would love

01:05:19.410 --> 01:05:22.510
to explore sometime
in the future.

01:05:22.510 --> 01:05:28.370
We also would love to explore
some crowdsourced improvement,

01:05:28.370 --> 01:05:30.300
the knowledge craft
that we have is --

01:05:30.300 --> 01:05:33.030
there are going to
be errors in it.

01:05:33.030 --> 01:05:34.330
That's the nature of how --

01:05:34.330 --> 01:05:36.670
what it looks like to bring
this material together,

01:05:36.670 --> 01:05:39.320
photographs miscategorized,
or things like that.

01:05:39.320 --> 01:05:41.890
So we'd love to have an
opportunity for people to,

01:05:41.890 --> 01:05:45.200
you know, help improve
that, especially in a field

01:05:45.200 --> 01:05:50.160
like baseball where there's
so many citizen experts

01:05:50.160 --> 01:05:52.250
who can help us do that.

01:05:52.250 --> 01:05:55.830
And then the last area for
opportunity, and again,

01:05:55.830 --> 01:05:59.070
we'll see when we
can explore these,

01:05:59.070 --> 01:06:00.900
is expanding the
concept beyond baseball.

01:06:00.900 --> 01:06:02.200
I mean, they are baseball cards

01:06:02.200 --> 01:06:04.300
but we can call them
trading cards.

01:06:04.300 --> 01:06:11.480
But the idea of using people
as an exploratory tool

01:06:11.480 --> 01:06:13.980
to multiple collections
is really exciting.

01:06:13.980 --> 01:06:16.980
This is sort of a front end to
some of the work that's being --

01:06:16.980 --> 01:06:19.950
that's working in linked
open data in Wikidata.

01:06:19.950 --> 01:06:23.560
And you could imagine the
same kind of exploratory tool

01:06:23.560 --> 01:06:29.350
for personages of the
Civil War or famous writers

01:06:29.350 --> 01:06:31.170
or anything like that.

01:06:31.170 --> 01:06:37.270
And so we'd be interested
in exploring any of those.

