01:39:19.940 --> 01:39:22.230
Would you share some maybe
things that you've seen recently

01:39:22.230 --> 01:39:24.890
in those spaces that
you think is either new

01:39:24.890 --> 01:39:26.190
or interesting about
communities?

01:39:26.190 --> 01:39:27.490
&gt;&gt; Clinton Yates: Yeah.

01:39:27.490 --> 01:39:28.870
I mean, I think one of the
the things that's forgotten

01:39:28.870 --> 01:39:32.440
about baseball is -- you know,
you can talk about the history,

01:39:32.440 --> 01:39:33.740
you can talk about the math,

01:39:33.740 --> 01:39:35.580
but in the sport itself
the communal contact

01:39:35.580 --> 01:39:36.880
of how it exists.

01:39:36.880 --> 01:39:39.100
Everybody has to watch
two people do one thing

01:39:39.100 --> 01:39:41.230
and that is a very interesting
relationship in terms

01:39:41.230 --> 01:39:44.550
of how it forces you to
understand the concept of team

01:39:44.550 --> 01:39:48.400
and the concept of performance
and the concept of failure in,

01:39:48.400 --> 01:39:50.730
you know, the communal sense.

01:39:50.730 --> 01:39:52.030
And I think that's a large part

01:39:52.030 --> 01:39:55.460
about why people attract
themselves, you know --

01:39:55.460 --> 01:39:58.180
baseball is attractive for
them and why it explains

01:39:58.180 --> 01:40:00.110
about how you have
to communicate.

01:40:00.110 --> 01:40:01.410
There's an umpire,
there's a manager.

01:40:01.410 --> 01:40:03.580
Everybody on the
bench wears a uniform.

01:40:03.580 --> 01:40:04.880
You know what I'm saying?

01:40:04.880 --> 01:40:06.910
Like it's very different
communication in terms

01:40:06.910 --> 01:40:12.290
of the basic fundamentals of
the game that I think apply

01:40:12.290 --> 01:40:14.340
to how people relate
to it, you know?

01:40:14.340 --> 01:40:17.780
So the laundry in one way is
very important in a certain way

01:40:17.780 --> 01:40:21.650
because you're not wearing
helmets, you know what I mean?

01:40:21.650 --> 01:40:22.960
You're not wearing shorts.

01:40:22.960 --> 01:40:24.900
You're wearing pants
and a shirt that button,

01:40:24.900 --> 01:40:26.340
and a belt, you know
what I mean?

01:40:26.340 --> 01:40:30.080
Like it is very much about a
sort of very normalized process

01:40:30.080 --> 01:40:32.670
that I think brings a
lot of people together.

01:40:32.670 --> 01:40:34.110
When you're talking
about social media

01:40:34.110 --> 01:40:38.900
and how different people come
toward it, everybody is allowed

01:40:38.900 --> 01:40:42.280
to like, as a result of all
those different things going on,

01:40:42.280 --> 01:40:44.100
a different part of
the game, you know?

01:40:44.100 --> 01:40:46.610
And that's very much, I
think, what attracts a lot

01:40:46.610 --> 01:40:47.910
of people to baseball.

01:40:47.910 --> 01:40:49.320
Most people who like
baseball probably --

01:40:49.320 --> 01:40:50.620
I say this all the time --

01:40:50.620 --> 01:40:52.460
probably never know how
to score a game, you know?

01:40:52.460 --> 01:40:55.670
But they enjoy the
environment around it.

01:40:55.670 --> 01:40:59.250
They enjoy the sounds
and sights of the game

01:40:59.250 --> 01:41:01.030
without even necessarily
caring what happens.

01:41:01.030 --> 01:41:04.750
And that's a large part
that baseball brings

01:41:04.750 --> 01:41:06.670
to the American sporting
landscape.

01:41:06.670 --> 01:41:09.670
And I think a lot of other
sports have not found a way

01:41:09.670 --> 01:41:10.970
to tap into it.

01:41:10.970 --> 01:41:14.280
And why, ultimately, it is
considered America's Pastime is

01:41:14.280 --> 01:41:16.530
because it doesn't
change much, you know.

01:41:16.530 --> 01:41:18.580
And people kind of like
that because people enjoy

01:41:18.580 --> 01:41:21.640
that in their communities.

01:41:21.640 --> 01:41:22.940
&gt;&gt; Meghan Ferriter:
Speaking about numbers

01:41:22.940 --> 01:41:25.390
