01:41:37.510 --> 01:41:40.420
So, Rob, I wonder if you
can reflect on the types

01:41:40.420 --> 01:41:43.200
of communities that formed
around baseball in Pittsburgh

01:41:43.200 --> 01:41:44.650
and some of your work
that you've shared

01:41:44.650 --> 01:41:47.070
about those types
of teams and people.

01:41:47.070 --> 01:41:48.930
&gt;&gt; Rob Ruck: I'm glad you're
not asking me a statistical

01:41:48.930 --> 01:41:50.230
question [laughter].

01:41:50.230 --> 01:41:51.530
&gt;&gt; Jordan Ellenberg: I'm here.

01:41:51.530 --> 01:41:52.830
Don't worry [laughter].

01:41:52.830 --> 01:41:55.550
&gt;&gt; Rob Ruck: Jordan's
got that covered.

01:41:55.550 --> 01:41:58.140
You know, I'm must more
interested in what sport means

01:41:58.140 --> 01:42:00.560
to people than the game itself.

01:42:00.560 --> 01:42:03.540
And when you look at a
place like Pittsburgh,

01:42:03.540 --> 01:42:06.180
where baseball was the sport,

01:42:06.180 --> 01:42:09.340
was the pastime,
for quite a while.

01:42:09.340 --> 01:42:12.030
No longer is.

01:42:12.030 --> 01:42:15.160
You see that it allowed
different groups of people

01:42:15.160 --> 01:42:18.070
to feel included in
a sense of community.

01:42:18.070 --> 01:42:22.150
I mean that whole notion of
baseball as the ultimate vehicle

01:42:22.150 --> 01:42:24.240
of Americanization
for the children

01:42:24.240 --> 01:42:28.230
of immigrants I think
is pretty valid.

01:42:28.230 --> 01:42:29.610
Where that broke
down, of course,

01:42:29.610 --> 01:42:31.970
was over questions of race.

01:42:31.970 --> 01:42:34.160
And during the half
century or so

01:42:34.160 --> 01:42:37.280
that the Major Leagues were
segregated Black Pittsburgh

01:42:37.280 --> 01:42:40.640
created a sporting
world of its own.

01:42:40.640 --> 01:42:43.920
And an amazing one, with
two Negro League franchises,

01:42:43.920 --> 01:42:48.120
seven of the first 11 men
from the Negro Leagues elected

01:42:48.120 --> 01:42:50.160
to the Hall of Fame
came from Pittsburgh,

01:42:50.160 --> 01:42:53.400
and many more ever since.

01:42:53.400 --> 01:42:57.270
But you look at that
community, that black community,

01:42:57.270 --> 01:43:00.510
which was fractured
by geography,

01:43:00.510 --> 01:43:03.640
by whether they were the Old
Pittsburghers who had come

01:43:03.640 --> 01:43:06.750
from the northern part of
the South in the 1890s,

01:43:06.750 --> 01:43:10.010
who were better off, better
educated, and lighter skinned,

01:43:10.010 --> 01:43:12.890
or those who came during
World War I and after

01:43:12.890 --> 01:43:15.570
from the Black Belt
who were not,

01:43:15.570 --> 01:43:18.690
you saw that it created
a sense of community

01:43:18.690 --> 01:43:22.710
for Black Pittsburgh
which allowed them,

01:43:22.710 --> 01:43:26.120
as the Negro Leagues
formed in the '20s,

01:43:26.120 --> 01:43:29.340
and had this archipelago
of franchises

01:43:29.340 --> 01:43:35.300
in these norther cities, to
feel a part of Black America.

01:43:35.300 --> 01:43:37.820
And I think that had a
profound impact on the ability

01:43:37.820 --> 01:43:41.440
to build cohesion and a positive
sense of collective self

01:43:41.440 --> 01:43:45.160
which lasted for quite a while.

01:43:45.160 --> 01:43:46.460
&gt;&gt; Meghan Ferriter:
Thank you very much

01:43:46.460 --> 01:43:47.960
for sharing more about that.

01:43:47.960 --> 01:43:50.050
During lunch today we
talked a little bit about --

01:43:50.050 --> 01:43:52.560
Clinton led us out
on this one --

01:43:52.560 --> 01:43:54.970
describing the ways
that professionalization

01:43:54.970 --> 01:43:58.430
of Major League sports may
make the sport less enjoyable.

01:43:58.430 --> 01:44:01.670
So I wonder if you can --
because it's predictable,

01:44:01.670 --> 01:44:03.320
I should say, not
less enjoyable,

01:44:03.320 --> 01:44:06.640
predictable in the sense of it's
routine, there's less variety,

01:44:06.640 --> 01:44:10.450
there's less excitement
over what might happen.

01:44:10.450 --> 01:44:13.500
And so I wonder if you, Clinton,
if you'd like to respond

01:44:13.500 --> 01:44:16.500
and maybe lead on your thoughts
on this, some of the ways

01:44:16.500 --> 01:44:21.130
that amateur sport or collegiate
sport and how baseball formed

01:44:21.130 --> 01:44:23.870
in those communities or in those
spaces tell us different kinds

01:44:23.870 --> 01:44:25.840
of stories than professional
sport.

01:44:25.840 --> 01:44:27.140
&gt;&gt; Clinton: Yeah.

01:44:27.140 --> 01:44:30.720
I think that's actually a
large part of why this sort

01:44:30.720 --> 01:44:33.530
of regionalization of
baseball has led to this sport

01:44:33.530 --> 01:44:35.300
at the highest level
of not being as popular

01:44:35.300 --> 01:44:37.510
as other leagues is that
Major League Baseball acts

01:44:37.510 --> 01:44:40.270
like they're the only form
of baseball that exists when,

01:44:40.270 --> 01:44:41.820
in reality, you look
at somebody like me.

01:44:41.820 --> 01:44:43.120
I grew up playing baseball.

01:44:43.120 --> 01:44:46.540
I played in RVI here in D.C.
I can name you, within a,

01:44:46.540 --> 01:44:48.180
you know, a couple
of relay throws,

01:44:48.180 --> 01:44:50.830
10 fields I played
on in the city.

01:44:50.830 --> 01:44:53.940
And that is what baseball
is to me, you know?

01:44:53.940 --> 01:44:55.680
People tell me all the
time, like oh, my god,

01:44:55.680 --> 01:44:56.980
how do you watch
college baseball.

01:44:56.980 --> 01:44:58.280
I can't deal with
the metal bats.

01:44:58.280 --> 01:44:59.580
Well, you must not have played
a lot of baseball growing up.

01:44:59.580 --> 01:45:01.320
I don't know anybody who's
playing wood bat leagues,

01:45:01.320 --> 01:45:02.670
you know what I'm saying,
when you're a kid, you know?

01:45:02.670 --> 01:45:03.970
That's not real.

01:45:03.970 --> 01:45:05.270
So what are you talking
about, right?

01:45:05.270 --> 01:45:07.360
And so what I'm saying -- and
the reason I bring that up is

01:45:07.360 --> 01:45:12.320
because it is -- it's
important to understand

01:45:12.320 --> 01:45:16.590
that like what you're referring
to in terms of the Negro Leagues

01:45:16.590 --> 01:45:19.860
and how that sense of community
came together was about more

01:45:19.860 --> 01:45:22.010
than just achievement
at the top.

01:45:22.010 --> 01:45:24.140
People played because they
liked playing baseball,

01:45:24.140 --> 01:45:26.010
and that's what's cool about it.

01:45:26.010 --> 01:45:27.730
You know, you go to
a high school game.

01:45:27.730 --> 01:45:29.590
People show up because their
kids are there to play.

01:45:29.590 --> 01:45:31.160
They don't plan to
go to college.

01:45:31.160 --> 01:45:33.070
They're not trying to
necessarily make the pro's.

01:45:33.070 --> 01:45:35.530
They enjoy spitting
seeds and talking trash

01:45:35.530 --> 01:45:37.910
with their friends, and
they enjoy hitting the ball

01:45:37.910 --> 01:45:39.210
and picking it up
and putting it down.

01:45:39.210 --> 01:45:41.470
And so if your only
sort of understanding

01:45:41.470 --> 01:45:45.540
of what the game is exists
from just the top level down,

01:45:45.540 --> 01:45:47.850
you're really selling
yourself short on a lot

01:45:47.850 --> 01:45:49.510
of what the community of
baseball is, you know.

01:45:49.510 --> 01:45:50.970
That's why I go to so
many minor league games.

01:45:50.970 --> 01:45:52.850
That's why I liked
coaching baseball,

01:45:52.850 --> 01:45:55.880
because you're involved
with it on a community level

01:45:55.880 --> 01:45:58.920
that is more than just about
the achievement, the contracts,

01:45:58.920 --> 01:46:01.200
the trophies, you
know, and the TV time.

01:46:01.200 --> 01:46:04.350
And that ultimately, to me,
is what gives back a lot more

01:46:04.350 --> 01:46:06.500
than any nonsense I
see on television.

01:46:06.500 --> 01:46:09.510
You know, it's knowing the
people I know from the game

01:46:09.510 --> 01:46:13.200
and what I was given
as a human in terms

01:46:13.200 --> 01:46:15.450
of understanding what it took
to, you know, make it work.

01:46:15.450 --> 01:46:17.740
And that's still something
that sticks with me.

01:46:17.740 --> 01:46:19.330
&gt;&gt; Jordan Ellenberg: I mean,
if I can jump in on that.

01:46:19.330 --> 01:46:20.630
&gt;&gt; Meghan Ferriter: Of course.

01:46:20.630 --> 01:46:21.990
&gt;&gt; Jordan Ellenberg: I mean,
but it's about this one thing.

01:46:21.990 --> 01:46:24.360
I mean, I -- because I spoke to
it in the story from this kind

01:46:24.360 --> 01:46:25.660
of top-down point of view.

01:46:25.660 --> 01:46:26.960
But it's very true that,
you know, if you're a fan

01:46:26.960 --> 01:46:28.650
of like your favorite sitcom
or something, you're not going

01:46:28.650 --> 01:46:30.870
to set up like four TV
cameras with your friends,

01:46:30.870 --> 01:46:32.410
like make your own
sitcom at home, right?

01:46:32.410 --> 01:46:34.940
I mean there's -- the only way
you're going to experience it is

01:46:34.940 --> 01:46:36.240
through the professional
[inaudible].

01:46:36.240 --> 01:46:37.540
&gt;&gt; Clinton Yates: You're talking
about YouTube, man [laughter].

01:46:37.540 --> 01:46:39.270
&gt;&gt; Jordan Ellenberg: No, it's
probably more now than before,

01:46:39.270 --> 01:46:41.700
but -- but, you know, as you've
seen with baseball, with respect

01:46:41.700 --> 01:46:43.810
to regionalization, you
know, I grew up in Maryland

01:46:43.810 --> 01:46:47.030
and hardly anybody I knew
played Little League.

01:46:47.030 --> 01:46:49.560
Like now I live in Wisconsin
and what I have learned is,

01:46:49.560 --> 01:46:52.450
you know, my son
plays and I go there

01:46:52.450 --> 01:46:54.630
and like there's parents
there whose kids are not even

01:46:54.630 --> 01:46:55.930
in the game.

01:46:55.930 --> 01:46:57.230
People in Wisconsin just --

01:46:57.230 --> 01:46:58.530
they'll just drive down to
the Little League field --

01:46:58.530 --> 01:46:59.830
&gt;&gt; Clinton Yates: Right.

01:46:59.830 --> 01:47:01.130
&gt;&gt; Jordan Ellenberg:
-- because you know one

01:47:01.130 --> 01:47:02.430
of your neighbor's kids is going
to be there and like, you know,

01:47:02.430 --> 01:47:03.730
you're going to see
people you know --

01:47:03.730 --> 01:47:05.030
&gt;&gt; Clinton Yates: Right.

01:47:05.030 --> 01:47:06.330
&gt;&gt; Jordan Ellenberg: --
or something like that.

01:47:06.330 --> 01:47:07.630
I mean -- so I think it
is like really different

01:47:07.630 --> 01:47:08.930
in different parts
of the country,

01:47:08.930 --> 01:47:10.510
and there you see this extremely
organic kind of fandom --

01:47:10.510 --> 01:47:11.810
or I shouldn't even
have called it a fandom,

01:47:11.810 --> 01:47:14.640
but an organic involvement
with baseball at --

01:47:14.640 --> 01:47:16.440
and if you think college
baseball is unpredictable,

01:47:16.440 --> 01:47:18.270
you know, watch --
the 12-year-olds,

01:47:18.270 --> 01:47:20.110
that's a different
story entirely.

01:47:20.110 --> 01:47:21.410
I mean --

01:47:21.410 --> 01:47:22.750
&gt;&gt; Clinton Yates:
Tell me about it, man.

01:47:22.750 --> 01:47:24.050
&gt;&gt; Meghan Ferriter: I'm thinking

01:47:24.050 --> 01:47:25.350
of two different
lines of thoughts.

01:47:25.350 --> 01:47:26.650
