01:47:26.650 --> 01:47:27.950
in the same [inaudible].

01:47:27.950 --> 01:47:29.250
I've heard a little bit
of mention here about some

01:47:29.250 --> 01:47:30.860
of the artifacts or objects of
baseball, some of the things

01:47:30.860 --> 01:47:33.630
that are -- metal bat
versus a wooden bat,

01:47:33.630 --> 01:47:36.500
the uniform that you wear,
what you're representing.

01:47:36.500 --> 01:47:38.800
And in some of our work at
the Library, we're looking

01:47:38.800 --> 01:47:40.390
at these collection items.

01:47:40.390 --> 01:47:41.690
We're thinking a
lot about the data.

01:47:41.690 --> 01:47:43.610
But there's also
the representation

01:47:43.610 --> 01:47:44.910
of [inaudible] as an image.

01:47:44.910 --> 01:47:46.680
What does that show us?

01:47:46.680 --> 01:47:50.120
And I wonder, Rob, if you can
share or reflect on how some

01:47:50.120 --> 01:47:53.290
of -- spaces of baseball
or items or objects

01:47:53.290 --> 01:47:56.050
of baseball are changing, and
how that connects to the types

01:47:56.050 --> 01:47:59.080
of -- the forms of baseball
that we see played today

01:47:59.080 --> 01:48:01.980
or other people have
played in the past.

01:48:01.980 --> 01:48:05.000
&gt;&gt; Rob Ruck: Most of the work
I've done on baseball's been

01:48:05.000 --> 01:48:08.350
in the Caribbean or
in black communities,

01:48:08.350 --> 01:48:13.130
looking at baseball pretty much
before integration [static].

01:48:13.130 --> 01:48:16.750
There's virtually no artifacts.

01:48:16.750 --> 01:48:19.120
What you have are memories.

01:48:19.120 --> 01:48:21.340
If you're lucky,
you find photos.

01:48:21.340 --> 01:48:24.060
The amount of footage is scant.

01:48:24.060 --> 01:48:30.710
I think, you know,
the last 25 years

01:48:30.710 --> 01:48:33.250
or so is baseball has
become overcapitalized.

01:48:33.250 --> 01:48:36.790
There's increasing stuff.

01:48:36.790 --> 01:48:39.220
But in some ways, to
me, it has less meaning.

01:48:39.220 --> 01:48:40.830
It's noise.

01:48:40.830 --> 01:48:44.690
The same way I feel when I go
to a Major League ballgame,

01:48:44.690 --> 01:48:49.020
which is why I don't feel it's
as enjoyable as a Minor League

01:48:49.020 --> 01:48:51.910
or a Caribbean or a
Little League game,

01:48:51.910 --> 01:48:55.090
because you can't even hear
the person next to you talk.

01:48:55.090 --> 01:48:57.400
You feel overwhelmed by it.

01:48:57.400 --> 01:49:01.070
So I'm probably not the one
to answer your question.

01:49:01.070 --> 01:49:03.200
&gt;&gt; Meghan Ferriter: Oh, I think
that's a perfect way to connect

01:49:03.200 --> 01:49:05.360
to spaces that may
be disappearing

01:49:05.360 --> 01:49:06.660
or still in [inaudible].

01:49:06.660 --> 01:49:10.000
Go ahead, Clinton.

01:49:10.000 --> 01:49:12.340
&gt;&gt; Clinton Yates: As
I was there recently

01:49:12.340 --> 01:49:13.640
and I wanted to point it out.

01:49:13.640 --> 01:49:14.940
My mother, who was
in the crowd --

01:49:14.940 --> 01:49:16.240
she's from Kansas
City, Missouri.

01:49:16.240 --> 01:49:18.100
And in Kansas City, the Negro
League Baseball Museum is there.

01:49:18.100 --> 01:49:20.890
Bob Kendrick is the
President of that facility.

01:49:20.890 --> 01:49:23.230
And what it does
is -- to your point

01:49:23.230 --> 01:49:26.200
about things being
scant, that is very true.

01:49:26.200 --> 01:49:27.580
There's not a ton.

01:49:27.580 --> 01:49:29.020
But there is a lot of it there.

01:49:29.020 --> 01:49:30.320
And what it does
that's interesting,

01:49:30.320 --> 01:49:31.730
and this is not necessarily
correlated.

01:49:31.730 --> 01:49:33.550
I just thought to bring it up.

01:49:33.550 --> 01:49:35.500
You realize that
what it chronicles is

01:49:35.500 --> 01:49:38.360
as much the history of
America as it is the history

01:49:38.360 --> 01:49:39.970
of many things necessarily
baseball.

01:49:39.970 --> 01:49:41.270
It really is, you know?

01:49:41.270 --> 01:49:43.160
And that's sort of
what you're --

01:49:43.160 --> 01:49:45.940
speaking to your point about how
sports affects people, you know,

01:49:45.940 --> 01:49:49.870
one of the first women owners in
sports was in the Negro Leagues.

01:49:49.870 --> 01:49:51.760
One of the first times
where they, you know,

01:49:51.760 --> 01:49:55.200
they played in those outside
view as communities first,

01:49:55.200 --> 01:49:57.820
be it the Caribbean, be in
Japan, be in wherever, you know?

01:49:57.820 --> 01:50:04.210
And it is scant, but it is
not non-existent, you know?

01:50:04.210 --> 01:50:07.090
And I think that's why
collections and things

01:50:07.090 --> 01:50:09.540
of this ilk are important
because everything

01:50:09.540 --> 01:50:10.840
at some point becomes scant

01:50:10.840 --> 01:50:12.140
because you can't
keep everything,

01:50:12.140 --> 01:50:13.440
you know what I mean?

01:50:13.440 --> 01:50:15.170
But there are collections
that do these jobs to keep

01:50:15.170 --> 01:50:17.720
around what, you know,
what people could.

01:50:17.720 --> 01:50:19.550
And it is, it's really
fascinating

01:50:19.550 --> 01:50:20.850
to look at, you know, this --

01:50:20.850 --> 01:50:22.300
&gt;&gt; Rob Ruck: To reinforce that.

01:50:22.300 --> 01:50:27.060
I mean, there's a reason
why Buck O'Neil was the star

01:50:27.060 --> 01:50:30.010
of Ken Burns's work on baseball,

01:50:30.010 --> 01:50:32.140
and I think a much
more important figure

01:50:32.140 --> 01:50:34.900
than Shelby Foote
in the Civil War.

01:50:34.900 --> 01:50:39.950
And Buck's memories and stories
and reflections steal the show.

01:50:39.950 --> 01:50:41.250
&gt;&gt; Clinton Yates: Yeah.

01:50:41.250 --> 01:50:43.730
&gt;&gt; Rob Ruck: But it underscores
how much your point is

01:50:43.730 --> 01:50:48.360
that questions of baseball are
questions of American history.

01:50:48.360 --> 01:50:51.550
And perhaps no more so
than when it comes to race.

01:50:51.550 --> 01:50:54.300
&gt;&gt; Jordan Ellenberg:
I'll, first of all,

01:50:54.300 --> 01:50:55.600
just second the recommendation

01:50:55.600 --> 01:50:57.860
of the incredible Negro
League Museum in Kansas City,

01:50:57.860 --> 01:51:00.010
which is like, I think, one
of the best history museums

01:51:00.010 --> 01:51:02.630
in America that I've been to.

01:51:02.630 --> 01:51:05.200
And then it's also to say I
think what you say is very

01:51:05.200 --> 01:51:07.090
right, and I think -- you
know, so I teach math.

01:51:07.090 --> 01:51:08.390
That's what I do for a living.

01:51:08.390 --> 01:51:12.070
And I find that one way
I tell stories about math

01:51:12.070 --> 01:51:13.920
as a teacher is to tell
stories about baseball

01:51:13.920 --> 01:51:15.940
because baseball touches
math like through statistics.

01:51:15.940 --> 01:51:18.330
And in the same way, I think,
you know, you teach history,

01:51:18.330 --> 01:51:20.890
Rob, and I think because
baseball touches so many things,

01:51:20.890 --> 01:51:25.100
as teachers one of the ways we
can teach whatever subject it

01:51:25.100 --> 01:51:27.550
is, like whether it's history,
whether it's sociology,

01:51:27.550 --> 01:51:30.940
whether it's African American
Studies, whether it's math.

01:51:30.940 --> 01:51:32.950
We can teach those through
the lens of baseball

01:51:32.950 --> 01:51:35.290
because baseball
touches them all.

01:51:35.290 --> 01:51:37.400
It's not just the story
of American history,

01:51:37.400 --> 01:51:38.700
but is the story of
American history.

01:51:38.700 --> 01:51:40.650
It's the story of like all
those things put together.

01:51:40.650 --> 01:51:43.020
And you can meet -- I mean,
you know, I meet a lot of kids

01:51:43.020 --> 01:51:44.440
who don't think they
care about math,

01:51:44.440 --> 01:51:45.740
but they know they
care about baseball.

01:51:45.740 --> 01:51:47.040
They know they care
about arguing

01:51:47.040 --> 01:51:48.340
about which player is
better than another.

01:51:48.340 --> 01:51:51.510
You may -- I mean, you know, a
kid who's a little kid today.

01:51:51.510 --> 01:51:52.880
You say, like, you
know, there was a time

01:51:52.880 --> 01:51:54.260
like when a black man
couldn't go to Woolworth's.

01:51:54.260 --> 01:51:55.560
They'll be like,
what's Woolworth's?

01:51:55.560 --> 01:51:56.860
&gt;&gt; Clinton Yates: Yeah.

01:51:56.860 --> 01:51:58.160
&gt;&gt; Jordan Ellenberg: Like
-- but if you say like,

01:51:58.160 --> 01:51:59.460
not everybody could play
Major League baseball.

01:51:59.460 --> 01:52:01.910
I mean that's -- I think
that's as meaningful

01:52:01.910 --> 01:52:03.210
and kids feel it as [inaudible].

01:52:03.210 --> 01:52:04.510
&gt;&gt; Clinton Yates: I was there.

01:52:04.510 --> 01:52:05.810
It's a huge discussion in
sports around the world, I mean,

01:52:05.810 --> 01:52:07.420
because I happen to be of
the opinion that anybody

01:52:07.420 --> 01:52:09.120
who played before
integration, I'm sorry,

01:52:09.120 --> 01:52:10.820
you're throwing your
records out, like I just --

01:52:10.820 --> 01:52:12.570
as a matter of course
they're not [inaudible].

01:52:12.570 --> 01:52:13.870
&gt;&gt; Jordan Ellenberg: And they
