of the experience is the biggest
patch of grass that a lot

02:12:37.370 --> 02:12:38.670
of people are ever going
to see in their lives

02:12:38.670 --> 02:12:39.970
in one place, you know?

02:12:39.970 --> 02:12:42.100
And [inaudible] people
should experience that.

02:12:42.100 --> 02:12:43.950
&gt;&gt; Rob Ruck: You know I think
that this thing about sports is

02:12:43.950 --> 02:12:46.890
when you're playing it yourself,
when you're participating.

02:12:46.890 --> 02:12:48.930
The next best thing
is when those

02:12:48.930 --> 02:12:51.840
who are competing are people
you know and care about.

02:12:51.840 --> 02:12:54.510
We get further and
further removed

02:12:54.510 --> 02:13:00.780
until we become these consumers
primarily on TV or on our phone

02:13:00.780 --> 02:13:06.490
or something, of people who
live in different zip codes.

02:13:06.490 --> 02:13:10.410
And I think if you flip it
historically with baseball,

02:13:10.410 --> 02:13:13.080
between World War I and
World War II there were 4-

02:13:13.080 --> 02:13:17.690
or 500 independent baseball
teams in Western Pennsylvania.

02:13:17.690 --> 02:13:22.250
The two Negro League
teams, you had the Pirates.

02:13:22.250 --> 02:13:24.240
But the independent sandlot

02:13:24.240 --> 02:13:27.420
and community teams drew
far more people each week

02:13:27.420 --> 02:13:30.130
than the professional clubs.

02:13:30.130 --> 02:13:33.860
And a lot of the people who
were playing were people

02:13:33.860 --> 02:13:37.710
who were playing into
their 40s or 50s,

02:13:37.710 --> 02:13:40.320
and 40 or 50 was relatively old.

02:13:40.320 --> 02:13:42.680
And they were playing
in the neighborhood

02:13:42.680 --> 02:13:46.390
where people could walk to
work, walk there after work,

02:13:46.390 --> 02:13:48.050
throw some money
in a passing hat,

02:13:48.050 --> 02:13:51.610
and either see people
they cared about

02:13:51.610 --> 02:13:53.530
or be a part of the action.

02:13:53.530 --> 02:13:57.340
And that to me is when sport
provides the most community.

02:13:57.340 --> 02:14:00.160
I think we've gotten several
steps removed from that.

02:14:00.160 --> 02:14:01.930
&gt;&gt; Meghan Ferriter: I want
to pick up on something

02:14:01.930 --> 02:14:03.230
that you mentioned
earlier, Clinton.

02:14:03.230 --> 02:14:04.560
And you and Jordan had a
little bit of a conversation

02:14:04.560 --> 02:14:06.390
about this, about some

02:14:06.390 --> 02:14:09.770
of the greatest players
playing before integration,

02:14:09.770 --> 02:14:11.070
and also the ways that --

02:14:11.070 --> 02:14:12.930
so we've got a couple of
press cuttings [inaudible].

02:14:12.930 --> 02:14:14.320
I only have two more questions.

02:14:14.320 --> 02:14:15.990
This is the second to last.

02:14:15.990 --> 02:14:21.190
So this is a question that's
about what types of patterns

02:14:21.190 --> 02:14:23.590
that you've seen in history,
Rob and Clinton and Jordan.

02:14:23.590 --> 02:14:27.310
And maybe you're thinking about
the numbers and what types of --

02:14:27.310 --> 02:14:30.860
what would you think is the
most important type of statistic

02:14:30.860 --> 02:14:37.570
or form of playing baseball or
pattern from players in the past

02:14:37.570 --> 02:14:39.870
that we've lost in today's game?

02:14:42.260 --> 02:14:44.450
&gt;&gt; Clinton Yates: Math Man.

02:14:44.450 --> 02:14:45.750
&gt;&gt; Jordan Ellenberg: Oh.

02:14:45.750 --> 02:14:49.840
I mean, if he means -- if
you really mean statistic,

02:14:49.840 --> 02:14:51.180
then I think the answer
is nothing I can --

02:14:51.180 --> 02:14:52.480
just statistical richness

02:14:52.480 --> 02:14:53.970
with which we understand
the sport today is just

02:14:53.970 --> 02:14:56.250
like vastly greater than it
was in any point in the past.

02:14:56.250 --> 02:14:58.030
So I actually think we
have everything we had

02:14:58.030 --> 02:14:59.330
in the past and like --

02:14:59.330 --> 02:15:00.630
&gt;&gt; Meghan Ferriter: Then
the numbers are consistent

02:15:00.630 --> 02:15:01.930
over time --

02:15:01.930 --> 02:15:03.230
&gt;&gt; Jordan Ellenberg:
And that's my point.

02:15:03.230 --> 02:15:04.530
&gt;&gt; Meghan Ferriter: -- and
other things have changed.

02:15:04.530 --> 02:15:05.830
&gt;&gt; Jordan Ellenberg: I mean,
well, apart from the fact that,

02:15:05.830 --> 02:15:07.860
you know, as Clinton brought
up, there was like differences

02:15:07.860 --> 02:15:09.650
in playing conditions like
literally who was allowed

02:15:09.650 --> 02:15:11.880
to play and who the competition
was and who was pitching to you.

02:15:11.880 --> 02:15:15.190
So that, obviously, is something
that you have to do separately

02:15:15.190 --> 02:15:17.910
from a numerical computation.

02:15:17.910 --> 02:15:20.350
But I think, you know, the
age of statistics that sort

02:15:20.350 --> 02:15:23.370
of really gets started in like
the late '70s, early '80s.

02:15:23.370 --> 02:15:25.050
Like when Bill James
goes big and sort

02:15:25.050 --> 02:15:27.000
of makes this a mass
market thing.

02:15:27.000 --> 02:15:28.760
&gt;&gt; Clinton Yates: Does everybody
here know who Bill James is?

02:15:28.760 --> 02:15:30.060
Is like that's just
a [inaudible].

02:15:30.060 --> 02:15:31.360
I mean --

02:15:31.360 --> 02:15:32.660
&gt;&gt; Jordan Ellenberg: I'm leaving

02:15:32.660 --> 02:15:33.960
that people don't
who Bill James is.

02:15:33.960 --> 02:15:35.260
I'm [inaudible].

02:15:35.260 --> 02:15:36.560
&gt;&gt; Clinton Yates: Why is that?

02:15:36.560 --> 02:15:37.860
I mean I --

02:15:37.860 --> 02:15:39.160
&gt;&gt; Jordan Ellenberg: Bill James
is the guy who brought kind

02:15:39.160 --> 02:15:40.460
of modern statistical
analysis of baseball.

02:15:40.460 --> 02:15:41.760
People were doing it, but Bill
James was the person who was

02:15:41.760 --> 02:15:43.810
like I can sell my books in
the B. Daltons and Waldenbooks.

02:15:43.810 --> 02:15:45.790
And maybe nobody knows
what B. Dalton [inaudible].

02:15:45.790 --> 02:15:47.730
&gt;&gt; Clinton Yates: We got
further away [laughter].

02:15:47.730 --> 02:15:49.030
&gt;&gt; Jordan Ellenberg: I'm the --

02:15:49.030 --> 02:15:52.890
like he was the guy who had
the kind of quixotic belief

02:15:52.890 --> 02:15:55.450
that like I can make this
like a mass market thing.

02:15:55.450 --> 02:15:57.650
And now, you know, you go
to Miller Park in Milwaukee.

02:15:57.650 --> 02:16:00.110
There's like OPS and WHIP
like on the scoreboard,

02:16:00.110 --> 02:16:01.410
on the big Diamond Vision.

02:16:01.410 --> 02:16:02.710
It's like right there
for everybody to see.

02:16:02.710 --> 02:16:04.570
I did not think I would see
that happen in my lifetime.

02:16:04.570 --> 02:16:05.870
&gt;&gt; Clinton Yates: Right.

02:16:05.870 --> 02:16:07.170
&gt;&gt; Jordan Ellenberg:
And I'm of the party --

02:16:07.170 --> 02:16:08.470
maybe it's obvious
that I would be --

02:16:08.470 --> 02:16:11.230
who thinks that's an
unalloyed good for baseball.

02:16:11.230 --> 02:16:13.830
I don't think that
replaces our fandom

02:16:13.830 --> 02:16:16.280
with spreadsheets
or number crunching.

02:16:16.280 --> 02:16:18.130
I think it just adds;
it doesn't subtract.

02:16:18.130 --> 02:16:19.430
&gt;&gt; Clinton Yates:
I'm really interested

02:16:19.430 --> 02:16:20.730
to hear what you think about
this in terms of the way

02:16:20.730 --> 02:16:23.250
that this statistical
forms of baseball has sort

02:16:23.250 --> 02:16:24.550
of overtaken -- I
mean, you know,

02:16:24.550 --> 02:16:25.850
between launching
[inaudible] and [inaudible]

02:16:25.850 --> 02:16:27.150
and all this other stuff.

02:16:27.150 --> 02:16:28.760
Like I imagine this is not
very popular in your world.

02:16:28.760 --> 02:16:31.150
&gt;&gt; Rob Ruck: Well, I
stopped understanding math

02:16:31.150 --> 02:16:34.030
after Woodstock [laughter],
and a lot of other things.

02:16:34.030 --> 02:16:35.330
&gt;&gt; Jordan Ellenberg: Wow.

02:16:35.330 --> 02:16:38.630
What did you take [laughter]?

02:16:38.630 --> 02:16:42.020
&gt;&gt; Rob Ruck: You know the --
when you look at all the stats,

02:16:42.020 --> 02:16:44.380
you just don't have
that for Black Baseball.

02:16:44.380 --> 02:16:45.680
&gt;&gt; Clinton Yates: Right.

02:16:45.680 --> 02:16:46.980
&gt;&gt; Rob Ruck: You don't have
that for the Caribbean.

02:16:46.980 --> 02:16:50.650
You're using a ball which
would have been thrown out if,

02:16:50.650 --> 02:16:52.380
you know, it was scratched

02:16:52.380 --> 02:16:54.640
or hit the ground
once in the majors.

02:16:54.640 --> 02:16:57.970
These guys might have played
most of a game with it.

02:16:57.970 --> 02:17:01.240
They're playing with
terrible lighting on fields

02:17:01.240 --> 02:17:03.900
that are not going to
give you a true hump.

02:17:03.900 --> 02:17:08.650
So the statistical stuff for
that era mean little to me.

02:17:08.650 --> 02:17:14.630
You know that Joe DiMaggio
can say Satchel Paige is the

02:17:14.630 --> 02:17:20.710
toughest pitcher he ever
faced, or when I would talk

02:17:20.710 --> 02:17:22.700
about the Negro Leagues
in Western Pennsylvania

02:17:22.700 --> 02:17:25.980
and have guys who played
for their coalminer team,

02:17:25.980 --> 02:17:29.240
white guys, stand up and
tell me how proud they were

02:17:29.240 --> 02:17:31.330
that Josh Gibson hit
a home run off them.

02:17:31.330 --> 02:17:32.630
&gt;&gt; Clinton Yates: Right.

02:17:32.630 --> 02:17:33.930
&gt;&gt; Rob Ruck: That
resonates with me.

02:17:33.930 --> 02:17:37.650
You know, the stuff
you see in box scores

02:17:37.650 --> 02:17:41.150
from those days --
it's shaky stuff.

02:17:41.150 --> 02:17:42.450
&gt;&gt; Clinton Yates: Right.

02:17:42.450 --> 02:17:43.750
And when I watch a
game now, I mean,

02:17:43.750 --> 02:17:46.160
the fun part is the stat --

02:17:46.160 --> 02:17:48.780
I mean the stats are part
of the game and the context

02:17:48.780 --> 02:17:52.390
of it is part of the notation,
it is part of the record.

02:17:52.390 --> 02:17:54.100
Like I said, I keep
score at games so that --

02:17:54.100 --> 02:17:57.090
that's sort of different
than statistics, obviously.

02:17:57.090 --> 02:17:58.670
But, you know, that's just --

02:17:58.670 --> 02:17:59.990
that's a part of the
game that I'm not going

02:17:59.990 --> 02:18:01.480
to say I don't care about
because that's not true.

02:18:01.480 --> 02:18:05.270
But it is not -- it is
behind the action, you know?

02:18:05.270 --> 02:18:07.260
And that's, that's -- but
that's also why it's cool,

02:18:07.260 --> 02:18:09.210
because you never -- you know,

02:18:09.210 --> 02:18:10.510
you don't remember
these things, you know.

02:18:10.510 --> 02:18:11.810
That's what they're there for.

02:18:11.810 --> 02:18:13.720
But, you know, the most
important stat to me is always

02:18:13.720 --> 02:18:15.650
when everybody forgets about
votes, which is runs scored.

02:18:15.650 --> 02:18:17.010
The player who scores
the most runs

02:18:17.010 --> 02:18:19.490
on a team is typically the best
player on the team [laughter],

02:18:19.490 --> 02:18:21.190
just so you know that.

02:18:21.190 --> 02:18:22.490
Yeah.

02:18:22.490 --> 02:18:23.790
&gt;&gt; Jordan Ellenberg: Actually,
can I -- I could have --

02:18:23.790 --> 02:18:26.550
I want to -- can I follow
up on that question, too?

02:18:26.550 --> 02:18:27.850
&gt;&gt; Meghan Ferriter:
You may, of course.

02:18:27.850 --> 02:18:29.150
&gt;&gt; Jordan Ellenberg: Am I
allowed to like usurp --

02:18:29.150 --> 02:18:30.450
&gt;&gt; Meghan Ferriter: Of course.

02:18:30.450 --> 02:18:31.750
&gt;&gt; Jordan Ellenberg:
-- momentarily.

02:18:31.750 --> 02:18:33.050
Okay. Because I think when I
think about what's different

02:18:33.050 --> 02:18:34.350
about the way the fans
today experience baseball --

02:18:34.350 --> 02:18:36.270
I don't think, actually, the
new regime of statistics makes

02:18:36.270 --> 02:18:37.570
that much different in how.

02:18:37.570 --> 02:18:38.870
I think, as you say, when
people are watching them

02:18:38.870 --> 02:18:40.290
when they watch the game is does
the guy cross the plate or not.

02:18:40.290 --> 02:18:41.590
And that's what they're
watching.

02:18:41.590 --> 02:18:44.610
But what I think is truly
different is to the extent

02:18:44.610 --> 02:18:47.450
that people's interaction
with the business

02:18:47.450 --> 02:18:49.820
of the sport is part
of their fandom.

02:18:49.820 --> 02:18:51.120
I mean, then you brought
it up when you talked

02:18:51.120 --> 02:18:53.500
about how it has become
more distant and more

02:18:53.500 --> 02:18:54.800
of a consumer operation.

02:18:54.800 --> 02:18:56.400
I mean, it kind of blows my
mind that my son, he's 12,

02:18:56.400 --> 02:18:58.210
he loves playing baseball
games on his phone.

02:18:58.210 --> 02:19:00.490
And he has one game where
he's like the hitter

02:19:00.490 --> 02:19:01.790
and a little pitch comes
and then he sort of tries

02:19:01.790 --> 02:19:03.090
to hit the phone
at the right time

02:19:03.090 --> 02:19:04.390
to make the bat hit the ball.

02:19:04.390 --> 02:19:06.390
But he has another game
where he's like the GM

02:19:06.390 --> 02:19:08.210
of a baseball team
and he has like --

02:19:08.210 --> 02:19:11.080
he thinks of both of those as
baseball games on the phone.

02:19:11.080 --> 02:19:12.380
You know what I mean?

02:19:12.380 --> 02:19:13.680
And I do think that
for this generation

02:19:13.680 --> 02:19:17.260
of fans thinking okay, like,

02:19:17.260 --> 02:19:19.930
how many compensatory draft
picks am I going to get

02:19:19.930 --> 02:19:21.230
if I trade this player
at this time?

02:19:21.230 --> 02:19:23.330
It's part of what they're
thinking about, not just like is

02:19:23.330 --> 02:19:24.630
that third baseman
going to like --

02:19:24.630 --> 02:19:25.930
&gt;&gt; Clinton Yates: Right.

02:19:25.930 --> 02:19:27.230
&gt;&gt; Jordan Ellenberg:
-- be able to like get

02:19:27.230 --> 02:19:28.530
over [inaudible]
to make that play.

02:19:28.530 --> 02:19:29.830
&gt;&gt; Clinton Yates: Yeah.

02:19:29.830 --> 02:19:31.130
&gt;&gt; Jordan Ellenberg: That's
a little bit foreign to me.

02:19:31.130 --> 02:19:32.430
And to me, I think that -- and
I'm curious what you guys think

02:19:32.430 --> 02:19:34.130
about that as -- in terms of
this next generation of fandom.

02:19:34.130 --> 02:19:35.690
&gt;&gt; Clinton Yates: The
League Manager is sort

02:19:35.690 --> 02:19:36.990
of what you're referring to.

02:19:36.990 --> 02:19:39.150
And there's games that are
based solely on that, you know,

02:19:39.150 --> 02:19:41.220
where you're not even playing
-- like video games, you know,

02:19:41.220 --> 02:19:44.100
like actual consoles, you know,
where that's all you're doing.

02:19:44.100 --> 02:19:46.160
That -- I don't need
that personally.

02:19:46.160 --> 02:19:47.460
I mean, that's not a knock.

02:19:47.460 --> 02:19:48.760
And I just -- I just don't --

02:19:48.760 --> 02:19:50.060
&gt;&gt; Jordan Ellenberg: This is

02:19:50.060 --> 02:19:51.360
like the old man
portion of the program.

02:19:51.360 --> 02:19:52.660
&gt;&gt; Clinton Yates: Oh, no.

02:19:52.660 --> 02:19:53.960
I mean [laughter] --

02:19:53.960 --> 02:19:55.260
&gt;&gt; Jordan Ellenberg: He's
worried about the [inaudible].

02:19:55.260 --> 02:19:56.560
&gt;&gt; Clinton Yates: I mean
I -- well, to be fair,

02:19:56.560 --> 02:19:57.860
I'd say the reason I don't do
it, because I'm not smart enough

02:19:57.860 --> 02:19:59.160
to get a handle on it.

02:19:59.160 --> 02:20:00.460
I mean, that's what
it comes down to.

02:20:00.460 --> 02:20:01.760
I mean, at the end of
the day I like playing

02:20:01.760 --> 02:20:03.060
because that was the easy part.

02:20:03.060 --> 02:20:04.360
Figuring out all this other
nonsense was hard, you know.

02:20:04.360 --> 02:20:05.660
So, that's not for me.

02:20:05.660 --> 02:20:06.960
&gt;&gt; Meghan Ferriter: Okay, one
last question and I'm going

02:20:06.960 --> 02:20:08.350
to connect it back to our
Collections at the Library.

02:20:08.350 --> 02:20:11.190
We recently digitized
Branch Rickey's papers

02:20:11.190 --> 02:20:12.840
and released them, so
anyone can explore them.

02:20:12.840 --> 02:20:15.610
And we heard a lot of
feedback publicly from people

02:20:15.610 --> 02:20:18.780
who were surprised and
excited to see different kinds

02:20:18.780 --> 02:20:21.500
of information within
the scouting reports

02:20:21.500 --> 02:20:22.800
and correspondence.

02:20:22.800 --> 02:20:25.520
And my question is,
what is an enduring myth

02:20:25.520 --> 02:20:28.120
that you think you would
like to either dispel

02:20:28.120 --> 02:20:31.850
or you recently myth-busted
yourself about baseball?

02:20:31.850 --> 02:20:33.150
&gt;&gt; Rob Ruck: Hmph.

02:20:33.150 --> 02:20:34.450
&gt;&gt; Clinton Yates:
Interesting question.

02:20:34.450 --> 02:20:36.750
&gt;&gt; Meghan Ferriter: You
can take your time today.

02:20:41.040 --> 02:20:42.460
&gt;&gt; Clinton Yates: Well, I
think a story worth noting

02:20:42.460 --> 02:20:44.770
about Branch Rickey that
may not necessarily go

02:20:44.770 --> 02:20:48.790
into the myth context
though, is that --

02:20:48.790 --> 02:20:50.850
I'm not going to say

02:20:50.850 --> 02:20:53.950
that integrating baseball was
not the most important thing

02:20:53.950 --> 02:20:55.250
that he did, because
I don't believe that.

02:20:55.250 --> 02:20:56.550
But people don't know
that Branch Rickey tried

02:20:56.550 --> 02:20:59.150
to start a third league like
the -- there was a whole --

02:20:59.150 --> 02:21:00.550
it was the National League,
there was the American League,

02:21:00.550 --> 02:21:01.880
and he tried to start
the Continental League.

02:21:01.880 --> 02:21:04.560
And I -- part like
-- I always think

02:21:04.560 --> 02:21:07.560
about what would have
happened if that had been real.

02:21:07.560 --> 02:21:08.860
You know what I'm saying?

02:21:08.860 --> 02:21:10.160
Like he had managed to --

02:21:10.160 --> 02:21:11.460
&gt;&gt; Meghan Ferriter: That
sounds like a great pilot.

02:21:11.460 --> 02:21:12.760
&gt;&gt; Meghan Ferriter: -- if he
had managed to pull that off,

02:21:12.760 --> 02:21:14.060
like we're just some
third league

02:21:14.060 --> 02:21:15.360
where the big leagues were
now, you know -- there was --

02:21:15.360 --> 02:21:17.820
I don't know, insert
15 more cities

02:21:17.820 --> 02:21:19.280
where there were just
Big League Teams now.

02:21:19.280 --> 02:21:20.580
That would have gotten
sort of subsumed

02:21:20.580 --> 02:21:21.880
into the large [inaudible].

02:21:21.880 --> 02:21:24.620
I think about that all the
time in terms of who he was

02:21:24.620 --> 02:21:26.870
because it was more -- like he
wasn't just some dude trying

02:21:26.870 --> 02:21:29.230
to get, you know, one
brother into the big's.

02:21:29.230 --> 02:21:30.530
That wasn't what he was.

02:21:30.530 --> 02:21:32.770
He was a totally larger
baseball mind in terms

02:21:32.770 --> 02:21:34.730
of so many different
things for a business

02:21:34.730 --> 02:21:37.380
and a growth standpoint.

02:21:37.380 --> 02:21:40.010
And that oddly gets
forgotten a lot, you know,

02:21:40.010 --> 02:21:41.310
which understandably --

02:21:41.310 --> 02:21:43.010
obviously Jackie Robinson's
importance to America and,

02:21:43.010 --> 02:21:44.480
you know, baseball is huge,

02:21:44.480 --> 02:21:45.950
and Branch Rickey's
involvement, and that was major.

02:21:45.950 --> 02:21:47.960
But that dude was much
bigger than that in terms

02:21:47.960 --> 02:21:52.580
of the specificity of the
sport and trying to grow it

02:21:52.580 --> 02:21:56.820
on an expansion level
in terms of [inaudible].

02:21:56.820 --> 02:21:59.810
&gt;&gt; Rob Ruck: Not to pile on
Branch too much, but you know,

02:21:59.810 --> 02:22:01.970
I think whoever described
him as the person

02:22:01.970 --> 02:22:05.860
who taught Machiavelli the
strike zone was on the money.

02:22:05.860 --> 02:22:07.600
And, you know, I thought
you were going to talk

02:22:07.600 --> 02:22:10.510
about the fact he built
a farm system in the '20s

02:22:10.510 --> 02:22:13.010
which monopolized
hundreds of kids --

02:22:13.010 --> 02:22:14.310
&gt;&gt; Clinton Yates: Right.

02:22:14.310 --> 02:22:16.190
&gt;&gt; Rob Ruck: -- for
the Cardinals.

02:22:16.190 --> 02:22:18.610
You know, Branch Rickey gets a
lot of credit, and I think a lot

02:22:18.610 --> 02:22:21.130
of it has been demolished
for integration.

02:22:21.130 --> 02:22:26.050
He's not doing it over
a social conscience --

02:22:26.050 --> 02:22:27.350
&gt;&gt; Clinton Yates: Right.

02:22:27.350 --> 02:22:28.650
&gt;&gt; Rob Ruck: -- question.

02:22:28.650 --> 02:22:30.520
He's doing it to monopolize
talent, win championships,

02:22:30.520 --> 02:22:34.380
and improve the bottom line.

02:22:34.380 --> 02:22:38.310
And, you know, to me a more
interesting proposition would

02:22:38.310 --> 02:22:40.550
be, what if they had brought

02:22:40.550 --> 02:22:44.750
in Negro League Clubs
in the late '40s?

02:22:44.750 --> 02:22:47.480
And the Negro League
Clubs, after integration --

02:22:47.480 --> 02:22:48.780
&gt;&gt; Clinton Yates: Yeah.

02:22:48.780 --> 02:22:51.270
&gt;&gt; Rob Ruck: -- which witnessed
their fanbase crumble overnight,

02:22:51.270 --> 02:22:53.450
petitioned Major
League Baseball --

02:22:53.450 --> 02:22:55.360
bring us in as a
high minor league.

02:22:55.360 --> 02:22:56.660
And [inaudible] didn't
even answer.

02:22:56.660 --> 02:22:59.860
And you could, you know
-- if that had happened,

02:22:59.860 --> 02:23:05.840
then you wouldn't have the
Al Campanis Movement in 1987

02:23:05.840 --> 02:23:10.590
where there's no black managers,
GMs, front office, or ownership.

02:23:10.590 --> 02:23:12.830
We're a little bit better
now, but not all that much.

02:23:12.830 --> 02:23:15.100
&gt;&gt; Clinton Yates:
Not by much at all.

02:23:15.100 --> 02:23:16.400
&gt;&gt; Meghan Ferriter:
Well, thank you so much

02:23:16.400 --> 02:23:17.960
for chatting with
me exclusively.

02:23:17.960 --> 02:23:19.980
Let's open up to
questions here in the room.

02:23:19.980 --> 02:23:23.660
Oh, we got one right
there, enthusiastic.

02:23:23.660 --> 02:23:25.660
So we have some microphones
for you to bring around.

02:23:25.660 --> 02:23:26.960
&gt;&gt; Rob Ruck: Water?

02:23:26.960 --> 02:23:28.260
&gt;&gt; Clinton Yates: Ah,
yes, please [inaudible].

02:23:28.260 --> 02:23:29.560
&gt;&gt; All right.

02:23:29.560 --> 02:23:30.860
Charles Martin.

02:23:30.860 --> 02:23:32.160
Thanks to Rob Ruck
again for your blurb

02:23:32.160 --> 02:23:33.540
on my book, <i>Lawyerball </i>.

02:23:33.540 --> 02:23:35.690
I'd like to make a statement

02:23:35.690 --> 02:23:41.380
and a proposal regarding
this stultifying conformity

02:23:41.380 --> 02:23:46.660
of baseball, the existential
turning point of baseball.

02:23:46.660 --> 02:23:50.700
I suggest that they
have the same --

02:23:50.700 --> 02:23:54.480
they relate to the same problem,
and they have the same solution

02:23:54.480 --> 02:24:00.340
which is that baseball,
thanks to the Major Leagues

02:24:00.340 --> 02:24:05.140
and to the Congress in
whose library we're sitting,

02:24:05.140 --> 02:24:11.360
is one of the few
legal, economic cartels.

02:24:11.360 --> 02:24:14.400
And Mr. Yates, the Continental
League would never have

02:24:14.400 --> 02:24:19.780
succeeded because baseball would
have used its 1922 Supreme Court

02:24:19.780 --> 02:24:24.810
Exemption in the
Anti-Trust Laws to kill it.

02:24:24.810 --> 02:24:27.810
This is how economic
cartels behave.

02:24:27.810 --> 02:24:29.490
They do no innovate.

02:24:29.490 --> 02:24:31.860
They kill competition.

02:24:31.860 --> 02:24:35.770
And the way to solve the
existential problem of people

02:24:35.770 --> 02:24:38.990
like Rob Ruck no longer enjoying
going to baseball games,

02:24:38.990 --> 02:24:43.090
baseball games taking three
hours, kids not knowing

02:24:43.090 --> 02:24:49.920
who Mazeroski and other people
in history are is competition.

02:24:49.920 --> 02:24:55.910
You introduce competition,
you will save the game.

02:24:55.910 --> 02:24:57.210
The game is great.

02:24:57.210 --> 02:24:58.510
It's hard to kill.

02:24:58.510 --> 02:24:59.810
But Major League Baseball

02:24:59.810 --> 02:25:02.040
and Congress are doing
their best to kill it.

02:25:02.040 --> 02:25:03.840
&gt;&gt; Clinton Yates: Is
this where we applaud?

02:25:03.840 --> 02:25:12.340
[ Applause ]

02:25:12.340 --> 02:25:13.780
&gt;&gt; Hi, this is Gates Ward.

02:25:13.780 --> 02:25:15.530
I was just wondering
if you ever think

02:25:15.530 --> 02:25:17.040
that we'll see a woman play

02:25:17.040 --> 02:25:19.480
in a non-exhibition Major
League Baseball Game?

02:25:19.480 --> 02:25:20.780
&gt;&gt; Rob Ruck: No.

02:25:20.780 --> 02:25:25.620
&gt;&gt; Clinton Yates: And I
think the reason for that is

02:25:25.620 --> 02:25:29.060
because I would rather just
watch women play baseball

02:25:29.060 --> 02:25:34.450
against other women than I would
necessarily some, you know,

02:25:34.450 --> 02:25:38.220
notion of egalitarianism
through competing against men.

02:25:38.220 --> 02:25:40.970
I like have a huge issue
with that on a lot of levels,

02:25:40.970 --> 02:25:42.270
mainly just because --

02:25:42.270 --> 02:25:44.860
for example, Serena Williams is
my favorite athlete of all time.

02:25:44.860 --> 02:25:46.780
Do I think she's the greatest
tennis play of all time.

02:25:46.780 --> 02:25:48.170
People like, you mean
for women, right?

02:25:48.170 --> 02:25:52.020
And I'm like, dog, that's
not -- first of all, no.

02:25:52.020 --> 02:25:56.350
And, secondarily, that's
not what that is, you know?

02:25:56.350 --> 02:26:01.700
And I would like to see
more opportunities for women

02:26:01.700 --> 02:26:03.070
to play baseball, period.

02:26:03.070 --> 02:26:06.620
And if it has to come only in
the world, in the framework

02:26:06.620 --> 02:26:12.510
of doing it against a man,
that's a major problem for me.

02:26:12.510 --> 02:26:17.010
[ Applause ]

02:26:17.010 --> 02:26:20.970
&gt;&gt; Questions relating
to the exhibit stairs.

02:26:20.970 --> 02:26:25.420
The first question is, the
exhibit really focused a lot

02:26:25.420 --> 02:26:27.000
on the evolution of baseball

02:26:27.000 --> 02:26:30.950
and I was wondering what
the panel's position was

02:26:30.950 --> 02:26:33.300
on the current changes
in the baseball rules,

02:26:33.300 --> 02:26:37.820
whether it be raising the
mound, as what, 20 years ago

02:26:37.820 --> 02:26:41.800
or introducing the DH,
or even the new rules

02:26:41.800 --> 02:26:43.800
that they're trying
to speed up the game

02:26:43.800 --> 02:26:46.170
by introducing differing things.

02:26:46.170 --> 02:26:49.020
As a historian or as
an ESPN commentator

02:26:49.020 --> 02:26:52.160
or as a mathematician
or statistician,

02:26:52.160 --> 02:26:55.510
how does that change the game
each time they introduce a new

02:26:55.510 --> 02:27:00.780
rule, or does it change the
game for the better or worse?

02:27:00.780 --> 02:27:02.080
&gt;&gt; Jordan Ellenberg: I mean,

02:27:02.080 --> 02:27:03.380
I'll just say this
as a mathematician.

02:27:03.380 --> 02:27:04.980
I value elegance a lot,
and I think this concept

02:27:04.980 --> 02:27:06.280
of having a runner start

02:27:06.280 --> 02:27:08.060
on second base is the most
cockamamie thing I've ever

02:27:08.060 --> 02:27:09.360
heard [laughter].

02:27:09.360 --> 02:27:11.090
I can't even say that it would
make the game better or worse.

02:27:11.090 --> 02:27:12.390
It's just ugly.

02:27:12.390 --> 02:27:13.690
And I don't like ugliness.

02:27:13.690 --> 02:27:17.930
So I oppose it on that ground.

02:27:17.930 --> 02:27:19.410
&gt;&gt; Clinton Yates:
I went to a game

02:27:19.410 --> 02:27:23.160
in Nashville probably a month
ago, and if you don't know this,

02:27:23.160 --> 02:27:25.090
in AAA they've got pitch clocks.

02:27:25.090 --> 02:27:26.980
It's -- what is it?

02:27:26.980 --> 02:27:32.390
It's 30 seconds between batters,
15 seconds between pitches,

02:27:32.390 --> 02:27:34.420
20 if there's a runner on base.

02:27:34.420 --> 02:27:37.100
And, okay, you know,
like whatever.

02:27:37.100 --> 02:27:38.870
Conceptually do I have
any problem with this?

02:27:38.870 --> 02:27:41.150
And I realized that my
only issue with it was

02:27:41.150 --> 02:27:42.790
that there's clocks
on the field.

02:27:42.790 --> 02:27:44.550
And like the huge cool
part about baseball is

02:27:44.550 --> 02:27:45.850
that there's no dang old clocks.

02:27:45.850 --> 02:27:47.150
And it's like the whole point.

02:27:47.150 --> 02:27:48.670
And there's like three
or four clocks around,

02:27:48.670 --> 02:27:51.810
so there's this sort of constant
countdown happening in your mind

02:27:51.810 --> 02:27:54.810
which was a little bothersome.

02:27:54.810 --> 02:27:58.280
But then they played
nine innings

02:27:58.280 --> 02:27:59.580
for like seven runs in the game.

02:27:59.580 --> 02:28:02.240
That bad boy was over in like
two hours and 15 minutes.

02:28:02.240 --> 02:28:04.860
I was like, whoa, okay.

02:28:04.860 --> 02:28:06.740
Like maybe I can kind
of deal with this.

02:28:06.740 --> 02:28:09.230
And so I'm not really sure

02:28:09.230 --> 02:28:12.150
because on the surface
it's annoying,

02:28:12.150 --> 02:28:13.990
but it worked, you know?

02:28:13.990 --> 02:28:15.290
It kept it moving.

02:28:15.290 --> 02:28:18.980
And if that's what your goal
is for baseball, then, sure.

02:28:18.980 --> 02:28:24.130
But my position on this has
always been that it's the nature

02:28:24.130 --> 02:28:28.340
of the game, batted balls and so
forth, that what happens on --

02:28:28.340 --> 02:28:30.280
during the course of the
game is what changes people's

02:28:30.280 --> 02:28:32.320
excitement, not just
the length of time.

02:28:32.320 --> 02:28:35.810
Inserting seven dudes between
the sixth and the ninth

02:28:35.810 --> 02:28:37.940
for [inaudible] is annoying,
you know what I mean.

02:28:37.940 --> 02:28:40.140
Like that's, that is
far more aggravating

02:28:40.140 --> 02:28:41.810
than just the amount
of time it takes.

02:28:41.810 --> 02:28:44.180
Instead you're constantly
stopping and starting,

02:28:44.180 --> 02:28:45.520
and what you're getting
isn't action.

02:28:45.520 --> 02:28:47.820
It's not, in fact,
that exciting.

02:28:47.820 --> 02:28:49.860
That to me is a larger issue
than people don't actually

02:28:49.860 --> 02:28:52.700
like what's happening, not
necessarily how long it's taking

02:28:52.700 --> 02:28:55.400
in any amount of time.

02:28:55.400 --> 02:28:56.700
&gt;&gt; Meghan Ferriter: Have we --

02:28:56.700 --> 02:28:58.000
have time I think for
-- oh, sorry, Jordan.

02:28:58.000 --> 02:28:59.300
&gt;&gt; Jordan Ellenberg: No,
that's okay [inaudible].

02:28:59.300 --> 02:29:00.600
&gt;&gt; Meghan Ferriter: One
more question if it's quick,

02:29:00.600 --> 02:29:02.680
and maybe another
one after that.

02:29:02.680 --> 02:29:05.790
&gt;&gt; Okay. I'll try
to make this quick.

02:29:05.790 --> 02:29:09.660
Do you think that the owners'
preoccupation with making money

02:29:09.660 --> 02:29:13.420
in the Major Leagues especially
has limited the availability

02:29:13.420 --> 02:29:17.020
for families, and obviously
it has, to go to the game?

02:29:17.020 --> 02:29:18.690
But the importance
of going to the game,

02:29:18.690 --> 02:29:22.230
having the same experience as
somebody like me that grew up

02:29:22.230 --> 02:29:25.280
and is 50 years old now,
would go to the game and end

02:29:25.280 --> 02:29:27.610
up behind Home Plate even
though I bought a ticket

02:29:27.610 --> 02:29:28.910
out in the outfield.

02:29:28.910 --> 02:29:31.090
And now if you try to go to
it and do that now and have

02:29:31.090 --> 02:29:33.910
that same experience of actually
hearing the communication

02:29:33.910 --> 02:29:36.460
between the dugouts and
the umpires and the batters

02:29:36.460 --> 02:29:39.100
and stuff is just -- you
don't have the same experience

02:29:39.100 --> 02:29:40.400
when you go to the
game and you go

02:29:40.400 --> 02:29:42.020
with family of four to a game.

02:29:42.020 --> 02:29:45.200
&gt;&gt; Jordan Ellenberg: I'll say
there's one thing I think modern

02:29:45.200 --> 02:29:47.960
baseball is doing right, and I'm
interested to hear your takes,

02:29:47.960 --> 02:29:51.170
too, is that I think the modern
baseball stadium, the cheap,

02:29:51.170 --> 02:29:52.570
faraway seats are really good.

02:29:52.570 --> 02:29:54.370
And that was not true when I
used to go to Memorial Stadium

02:29:54.370 --> 02:29:55.670
as a kid in Baltimore.

02:29:55.670 --> 02:29:58.050
I got to Miller Park now and
I go to Camden Yards now.

02:29:58.050 --> 02:30:00.490
I buy an -- I mean, I like to
buy an expensive seat sometimes,

02:30:00.490 --> 02:30:01.790
show off my kids, whatever.

02:30:01.790 --> 02:30:04.980
But like I -- if I sit in
the bleachers it's still --

02:30:04.980 --> 02:30:07.430
you really feel in the game, and
think it was way that was not

02:30:07.430 --> 02:30:08.730
as true in the older stadiums.

02:30:08.730 --> 02:30:10.500
So in that one respect I
actually think they're doing

02:30:10.500 --> 02:30:12.440
more to equalize the
experience [inaudible] more,

02:30:12.440 --> 02:30:13.740
and people [inaudible] less.

02:30:13.740 --> 02:30:15.040
&gt;&gt; Clinton Yates: That's
an excellent point.

02:30:15.040 --> 02:30:16.340
I hadn't ever really
though of it that way,

02:30:16.340 --> 02:30:18.270
which is that the
stratification between the best

02:30:18.270 --> 02:30:20.560
and the worse is not
necessarily that different.

02:30:20.560 --> 02:30:21.860
You know what I mean?

02:30:21.860 --> 02:30:23.160
I hate sitting behind the plate.

02:30:23.160 --> 02:30:24.680
For me it's a bad
view, and I'm not --

02:30:24.680 --> 02:30:25.980
you know, you're
looking through a net.

02:30:25.980 --> 02:30:27.930
Like I don't actually
like that seat.

02:30:27.930 --> 02:30:30.390
But I do think there's
something to be said

02:30:30.390 --> 02:30:33.410
about the family experience.

02:30:33.410 --> 02:30:34.810
But, I mean, when I
go to baseball games,

02:30:34.810 --> 02:30:36.760
like I really kind
of only see families.

02:30:36.760 --> 02:30:38.060
Like I don't -- you know,

02:30:38.060 --> 02:30:41.300
I'm not really sure what the
other side of that complaint is

02:30:41.300 --> 02:30:43.510
because while, yes, it
is extremely expensive

02:30:43.510 --> 02:30:46.630
in the basic context of the
value of a dollar, like I don't

02:30:46.630 --> 02:30:50.970
like -- I don't know who
else is going to ballgames.

02:30:50.970 --> 02:30:52.270
You know what I'm saying?

02:30:52.270 --> 02:30:53.570
It's not like people are
just walking off the street

02:30:53.570 --> 02:30:55.860
that much necessarily
outside of, you know,

02:30:55.860 --> 02:30:57.860
random businessmen specials or
whatever, which, by the way,

02:30:57.860 --> 02:30:59.160
I still never understand.

02:30:59.160 --> 02:31:00.460
Like businessmen's specials.

02:31:00.460 --> 02:31:02.140
Like what -- why is it called
that, you know what I mean?

02:31:02.140 --> 02:31:03.440
Is it dudes leaving their aunt?

02:31:03.440 --> 02:31:04.740
Like what is this, you know?

02:31:04.740 --> 02:31:06.460
That's such an --
[inaudible] integrated terms.

02:31:06.460 --> 02:31:07.760
That is an integrated one.

02:31:07.760 --> 02:31:09.060
But I guess what I'm saying --

02:31:09.060 --> 02:31:10.530
that there is still a lot of
families going to ballparks and,

02:31:10.530 --> 02:31:15.060
you know, without delving
into the intense economics

02:31:15.060 --> 02:31:19.250
of why it costs so much
to go to games, you know,

02:31:19.250 --> 02:31:20.570
it's still a fun experience.

02:31:20.570 --> 02:31:23.000
And that to me is
hard to evaluate.

02:31:23.000 --> 02:31:24.830
Like if you don't like
it, you don't like it.

02:31:24.830 --> 02:31:26.130
But if you go there,

02:31:26.130 --> 02:31:27.800
you're probably going
to have a good time.

02:31:27.800 --> 02:31:30.100
And that to me is, I guess,

02:31:30.100 --> 02:31:32.570
effectively the most
important thing overall.

02:31:32.570 --> 02:31:34.210
No? I mean is that --
does that make sense?

02:31:34.210 --> 02:31:36.620
&gt;&gt; Rob Ruck: I would
just add that I think

02:31:36.620 --> 02:31:38.630
that the smart franchises

02:31:38.630 --> 02:31:41.920
in the smart sports
are cultivating kids,

02:31:41.920 --> 02:31:43.800
and building them as fans.

02:31:43.800 --> 02:31:46.770
And I've seen the Penguins
do that in Pittsburgh

02:31:46.770 --> 02:31:49.730
by making a large block
of tickets available

02:31:49.730 --> 02:31:53.180
at moderate prices
to college students

02:31:53.180 --> 02:31:55.580
and the success of
the team itself.

02:31:55.580 --> 02:31:57.590
But you know I think,
for example,

02:31:57.590 --> 02:32:00.480
in the Dominican Republic, where
you go to some [foreign words]

02:32:00.480 --> 02:32:04.590
and before a game you
see 30 or 40 kids seated

02:32:04.590 --> 02:32:08.430
on the outfield walls
with poles with nets

02:32:08.430 --> 02:32:11.410
at the end to try to snag balls.

02:32:11.410 --> 02:32:18.110
And they become lifelong
fans in the process.

02:32:18.110 --> 02:32:19.410
&gt;&gt; Meghan Ferriter: Great.

